[White "1. Introduction"]
[Black "Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Robert James Fisher believed that it's possible to get an advantage only after 1.e4. Many years have passed since then, chess has made 180 degree-change with the advent of the computer, but it seems to me that old Fischer was right after all. }
1... c5 2. Nc3
{ One of the questions I asked myself as a player who has played the Sicilian Defense for Black for almost all his life is “What move am I afraid to see on the board after 1. e4 - c5?”. The answer was more than obvious - 2. Nc3! Closed Sicilian! This opening was so unpleasant for me that sometimes when preparing for the game if I saw an opponent playing the Closed Sicilian, I just played something else on the first move. I don’t want to be a liar, so, objectively, with the best black play, you will not have an advantage. But ask yourself one question: “Do I constantly play with players FIDE rating 2500+ ?”. If your answer is yes, then most likely you should not play this opening. But even in this case, you can successfully use it as a second opening. If your answer is no, then this is exactly what you need! One of the most difficult tasks in chess is choosing an opening that will completely suit you in the character and the style. Most of my students have difficulty choosing a plan after an opening. Playing Closed Sicilian, you will no longer have this problem. White’s plans are logical, usually, they are connected with the attack on the kingside. Everyone likes attacking the opponent's king, doesn’t it? And their study is easier in comparison with other openings. Despite the fact that Black can equalize in some variations, the Closed System requires Black to solve constantly emerging problems by himself, which is already a good achievement in modern chess. Sometime after you start playing the Closed Sicilian, you will be able to feel more subtly when you need to play f2-f4-f5, when to put the Knight on f4 or in advance to neutralize the opponent's counterplay attempts on the queenside. Good luck learning the Closed Sicilian! }
