1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 Nge7
{ In the previous line, we discussed the early ...Rb8 move. The equally popular move ...Nge7 is the most logical and natural move in this position from the point of view of simple chess understanding. Black develops a minor piece and prepares to make a kingside castle. It would seem, what could be the drawback of this move? }
8. Bh6
{ The h6 square becomes unprotected, so we are very happy to exchange the strong fianchettoed Bishop on g7. Black's kingside pawns are located on light squares, which means that exchanging the dark-squared Bishops is definitely beneficial for White. }
8... O-O
{ The most popular and simplest solution, although dangerous. White's cannons are already loaded, and the Black King voluntarily goes into the thick of the battle. }
9. h4
{ We start the attack as soon as possible. This is a standard attack plan against such a kingside pawn structure. In a military battle, it is important to use all the guns, and in a chess game, all the pieces. With the h4-move, we want to push the pawn even further and open the h-file, thus involving the Rook into play. }
9... f6
{ The strongest move! Black prepares ...g5, preventing the opening of the h-file.  In case of careless   9. ...f5?  White can continue the attack smoothly  10.h5  Rf7  11.hxg6  hxg6  12.Nf3  Including all pieces in the attack.  12. ...Qf8  13.Bxg7  Qxg7  14.Ng5  Rf8  15.O-O-O  Ne5  16.Rh7  Qf6  17.Rdh1  And Black's position is almost hopeless }
10. Bxg7 { Exchanging the main defender of the Black fortress. } 10... Kxg7 11.
h5
{ Although opening the h-file will most likely fail, it is important to provoke Black to advance the pawns on the kingside, which makes the King's position weak. }
11... g5 12. h6+
{ Black wanted to play ...h6, creating a fairly strong pawn chain that would not be easy to break. Therefore, we must disrupt the coordination of Black pieces and make the pawn on g5 more vulnerable. }
12... Kh8 { The safest square for the King at the moment. } 13. f4
{ The g5 pawn has been advanced unforgivably far, so we don't miss a chance to attack it and open the kingside. }
13... gxf4 { The most natural move. } 14. gxf4
{ Of course, we take with a pawn without disturbing the harmony of our pawn structure. }
14... Rb8
{ I think this is Black's most principled move. Black is preparing the b5 advance, the most common plan in the Closed Sicilian. }
15. Nf3
{ After the pawn is already on f4, it's a good idea to develop the Knight to f3. 'Pawns in front, pieces to the rear' as Philidor wrote. }
15... b5 { Black starts his attack on the queenside. } 16. e5
{ Attack of the most defended square! We want to open the position even further, while simultaneously destroying Black's pawn structure. }
16... dxe5
{ In my opinion, the capture by the d-pawn is a little safer, since Black leaves one pawn on the kingside. }
17. fxe5 f5 18. O-O-O
{ Before starting active actions on the kingside, we need to secure our own King. }
18... Ng6 19. Ne2
{ We are transferring the Knight to the kingside and preparing the transfer of the Queen to the c3-square in case of the capture of the e5-pawn. }
19... b4 20. d4
{ An unexpected breakthrough in the center! The pawn on e5 is now protected, and in case of a capture, we will control the d-file. }
20... c4 21. Qg5 { Offering to exchange Queens. } 21... Bb7 22. Rhg1
{ Occupying the open g-file. The endgame will be more favorable for White due to more active pieces, more space in the center and on the kingside, and a weak pawn on e6. }
