1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e5
{ It seems to me that this is the strongest continuation, but fortunately only the fourth most popular. The main idea behind ​​this move is to grab the space in the center and support the move Nd4. At the same time, this move should not be overestimated. The d6 pawn becomes weak and the dark-squared Bishop is at least temporarily blocked. }
7. f4
{ In comparison with other variations, we don't play Qd2 immediately, but first f4, in order to develop the Knight on f3 as soon as possible. }
7... Nge7
{ Black, in turn, decides to develop the Knight on e7 so as not to block the dark-squared Bishop and to be able to move the f-pawn. }
8. Nf3 { Developing the Knight and threatening to take on e5. } 8... Nd4
{ The strongest move! Black not only centralizes the Knight but also blocks the g1-a7 diagonal, making it possible to capture on e5 with a pawn. }
9. O-O O-O 10. Qd2
{ The mobilization of forces is over and the middlegame begins. Black has a large number of different continuations. }
10... Bg4
{ The most popular move. Black wants to 'double' the Queen and the Bishop along the c8-h3 diagonal. }
11. Nh4
{ If Black has such a pawn triangle, that is, the pawns are on c5, d6, and e5, then one of the best and most dangerous plans is to advance f4-f5. Even though the Knight is placed at the edge of the board, it will help us carry out this plan. }
11... exf4 12. Bxf4
{ Unfortunately, it is no longer possible to play f5, but on the other hand, Black exchanged the central e-pawn for the side f-pawn, opening the f-file along the way. }
12... Qd7 13. Rf2 { With the idea of ​​doubling the Rooks along the f-file. }
13... Rae8 14. Bh6 { With the idea to exchange the strong Bishop. } 14... Bxh6
15. Qxh6
{ Here Black's position is already unpleasant, as the Queen on h6 creates a dangerous initiative. }
15... b5 16. h3
{ Driving the Bishop out of our half of the board and inviting Black into a small trap.   16. ...Bxh3??  This would be a critical mistake  17.Nf3!  Attacking the Bishop and threatening to play Ng5 at the same time.  17. ...Bxg2  18.Ng5  +-  Qxh7 is an unstoppable threat. }
16... Be6 17. Raf1 { Putting more pressure on the f-file. } 17... Nec6
{ The best move for Black according to the engine but never played before. }
18. Nf5 { A great combination! } 18... f6 19. Ne3
{ The Knight will be excellent on the outpost. } 19... Qg7 20. Qxg7+ Kxg7 21.
Ncd5 { We are going to attack the d4 Knight and enjoy our Knight on d5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
