1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nd4
{ A rare move, but it was played by Garry Kasparov during his peak years in the game with Nigel Short, which means it deserves attention. Black's idea is to postpone the development of the kingside and start immediate actions on the queenside. }
7. Qd2 Qa5 8. f4
{ Since White can't play the typical move Bh6 in these positions in the near future, we play f4! An active move that will allow us to develop the Knight to f3. }
8... e6 9. Nf3 Ne7 10. O-O Nec6 11. e5
{ A typical move for the Closed Sicilian and was played by Short against Kasparov. We are trying to take advantage of the weak defense of Black's kingside and open up the position. }
11... dxe5 12. Nxe5
{ It's important to capture the pawn with the Knight, otherwise, the intermediate capture Nf3 will follow. }
12... O-O
{ 12...Nxe5  The most principled continuation - Black accepts the pawn sacrifice.  13.fxe5  Bxe5  14.Qf2  We're directly attacking the f7-pawn and indirectly creating pressure on the c5-pawn.  14...O-O  15.Ne4  We strengthen the position of the Knight, creating a large number of threats. For example, we want to play c3 or Nf6.  15...Nf5    Black takes the Knight away from the d4-square in advance and blocks the f-file, but loses the pawn on c5.  16.Bxc5  Qxc5  An unusual way to exchange Queens.  17.Nxc5  Bd4  18.g4  We force Black to take on f2 immediately.  18...Bxf2+  19.Kxf2  We need to place the King closer to the center in the endgame.  19...Nd6  20.Ke3  +=  We are finishing the centralization of the King and want to grab the center by d4. }
13. Bxc6
{ Improving the game Short - Kasparov. Even better than Qf2 with the transition to the previous sideline. }
13... Nxc6 14. Qf2 { We are attacking the c5-pawn now. } 14... Nd4
{ Such a loss of time cannot but affect the evaluation of the position.   14. ...Nxe5  Accepting a pawn sacrifice leads to the loss of exchange.  15.fxe5  Bxe5  16.Bxc5  ±  And the Black Rook is chained to defend the f7-pawn. }
15. Ne4 { Transferring the Knight to the center and intending to play c3 }
15... f6 16. Nc4
{ We retreat with the Knight, attacking the Queen at the same time. } 16... Qc7
17. c3 Nc6 18. Bxc5 { Black doesn't have any compensation for the pawn. } *

