[Black "Smyslov variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6
{ Black tries to save the move ...d6 in order to make the move ...d5 without losing a tempo. }
6. Be3
{ Of course, White disrupts this plan, and now the c5-pawn is under attack. The move ...d6 leads to the main variation 5. ...d6. }
6... Nd4
{ Black improves the position of the Knight and defends the c5-pawn at the same time. }
7. Nce2
{ This is a critical starting position -'tabia'. This move was played by the world champion Vasily Smyslov several times in 1946 and 1947. I think that this variation deserves to be named after Smyslov. We are trying to drive off the strong d4-Knight as quickly as possible. Black has several continuations. }
7... Ne7 8. c3
{ This is the idea behind the move Nce2 - to free the c3 square for the pawn. }
8... Nxe2 9. Nxe2 d6
{ The most natural and popular way to defend the c5-pawn. } 10. Qd2
{ There was nothing wrong with playing d4 again, but unlike 9. ... b6 variation, White no longer has the idea to play Qd6. }
10... O-O 11. h4 { Let's start our typical attack. } 11... Nc6 12. h5 Ne5
{ Black's plan is to transfer the Knight on g4 and to exchange the dark-squared Bishop. }
13. O-O-O
{ The logical move   13.Bh6?  would be a blunder due to  13. ...Bxh6  14.Qxh6  g5!  avoiding opening the h-file and intending to trap the Queen with ...Ng4.  15.f4  the only way to free the Queen.  15. ...Nxd3  16.Kd2  Nxb2  Black is a pawn up and the White King is exposed. }
13... Ng4 14. Kb1
{ In Kyiv, as in many other cities of Ukraine, where I am from, there is a place in the central park where chess fans get together. If you suddenly decide to play a couple of games there, then be careful, because some experienced 'amateurs' manage to play queenside castling and Kb1 in one move. On the one hand, this is cheating, but on the other hand, it is a sign of great positional understanding! }
14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Rb8 16. d4
{ The exchange of the dark-squared Bishop is compensated by complete domination in the center. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter guide"]
[Black "2. ... Nc6 3. ... e6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 e6
{ A completely different plan. Earlier we considered the lines where Black fianchettoes the dark-squared Bishop, puts the Knight on d4 and attacks on the queenside. In this line, Black develops the Bishop to e7 with the plan of playing ...d5. }
4. Bg2 Nf6 { The most active continuation. } 5. d3 Be7 6. Nge2
{ Although the most popular move is f4, I find it too optimistic. It is quite difficult to create an attack on the kingside, because Black doesn't have pawn weaknesses there, such as the g6-pawn, for example. Therefore, we need to concentrate our play in the center and develop the pieces as fast as possible. }
6... O-O 7. O-O
{ There is no need to rush to develop the dark-squared Bishop because it is not known yet what our plan will be - to play Bg5 or f4. }
7... d5
{ The main idea of the move 3...e6 is to hit in the center with ...d5. } 8.
exd5 exd5
{ Of course, Black's central pawns look very nice, but it's important not to forget that the further the pawn is advanced, the more vulnerable it is. }
9. Bg5
{ With a concrete idea, either to win the central pawn on d5 by Bxf6 and Nxd5 or to play d4, fixing an isolated pawn. }
9... d4
{ Recently, I have concluded that every move in chess is an exchange. It sounds strange, doesn't it? It is useful to examine this question by reference to a concrete example. Black played ... d4. Is this a taking of a piece? Obviously not. Black opened the h1-a8 diagonal for White's light-squared Bishop and gave the e4-square to White's Knight. In return, Black grabbed some space in the center and made the d-pawn defended. Although this is not a capture, I still think that this is an exchange. And assessing the consequences of such an exchange is quite difficult. }
10. Bxf6
{ This useful intermediate capture allows us to occupy the e4 square with our Knight. }
10... Bxf6 11. Ne4 { The c5-pawn is under attack. } 11... Be7 12. Nf4
{ It is common to use the term 'the Bishop pair advantage', but I think in this case we can say that White has the Knight pair advantage. The Knights are beautiful. }
12... Bf5 13. Re1
{ It is a good idea to place a Rook on an open file, even if no specific threat is created. }
13... Rc8 14. Qh5
{ We're invading the opponent's half and provoking Black some weaknesses near the Black King. }
14... g6 15. Qh6
{ But the position of the Black King is really alarming now. We want to play Nd5 on the next move. }
15... Nb4 16. Re2
{ We defend the c2-pawn and we are going to double the Rooks on the e-file. White is slightly better thanks to strong Knights, weakness on the kingside, and control of the e-file. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter guide"]
[Black " 2. ... e6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ The idea behind this move is to play ...d5 as soon as possible. } 3. g3 d5
{ Although this variation has been played by many grandmasters, I think I managed to find a pleasant advantage for White. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. d4
{ The second most popular, but conceptual move! The pawn on d5 is an obvious weakness since it can't be defended by another pawn, so we fix it with d4. White's key idea in this variation is to play against the weakness on d5. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nf6 { The only reasonable move. } 7. Bg5
{ We're pinning the Knight, the defender of the d5-pawn. A pin in itself is a good idea, though. }
7... Be7
{ It seems that White can immediately win the pawn by 8. Bxf6 - Bxf6 9. Qxd5. But a strong intermediate move 9. ... - Bxс3! follows and it's time for the White to resign. }
8. O-O-O
{ Of course, this variation is very different from the standard positions of the Closed Sicilian. And I can't even call this position a closed one. Since the variation is different, then the plans are also different. Queenside castling is not a typical move for the Closed Sicilian, but this move is definitely good now because we are hiding the King and creating pressure along the d-file at the same time. }
8... Nc6 9. Qa4
{ The best square for a Queen is one from which it can't be kicked out! In addition, the black Knight is pinned. }
9... Be6 10. Bg2
{ Developing the Bishop and increasing the pressure on the d-pawn. } 10... O-O
11. Nge2 { With a threat to play Nf4. } 11... Qb6 12. Rhf1
{ Don't forget about the f2-pawn! } 12... Rac8 13. Be3 Bc5 14. Bxc5
{ Playing against or with an isolated pawn requires, if not a book, then at least a large chapter in it. But in short, when we play against an isolated pawn, we need to: attack it with all our forces; if possible, block it; trade minor pieces. The last point is especially important because this is the only way we can extinguish the enemy's attack fire. Therefore, we are happy to exchange the dark-squared Bishops. }
14... Qxc5 15. Qb5 { The exchange of Queens also doesn't hurt. } 15... Qxb5 16.
Nxb5 Rfd8 17. Rfe1
{ Followed by blocking the d5-pawn by Nbd4. We managed to prevent the activity of Black pieces and block the isolated pawn. Black is unlikely to be able to get rid of the weakness on d5, so White has a pleasant long-term advantage.  The annoying move   17. ...Ng4  fails to  18.Nf4!  Nxf2  19.Rd2  Ne4  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.Nd6!  +- }
