[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter guide"]
[Black "2. ... Nc6 3. ... d6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 d6
{ By making this move Black refuses to advance d5 in the near future. } 4. Bg2
{ The most popular move ...g6 transposes to the main line 3. ... g6 } 4... Nf6
5. d3 e6 6. Nge2
{ I prefer to develop the Knight on e2 rather than on f3 because later we can move the Knight to g3, where it will perfectly support the attack. }
6... Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3
{ An excellent prophylactic move. We're not only permanently closing the road to g4 for the Black Knight, but also prepare the move g4. }
8... Rb8 { Black is preparing an attack on the queenside. } 9. f4
{ We're not only starting the attack on the kingside but also preventing ...b5. }
9... Bd7 { A possible way to protect the Knight on c6. } 10. g4
{ The most tempting and best move! } 10... b5
{ Black isn't wasting any time as well and starting the attack on the queenside. }
11. Ng3
{ The Knight is excellently placed on g3. In the future, we can play f5 or Nh5. }
11... b4 12. Nce2 Ne8 13. a3
{ Useful inclusion of moves. Without losing a single tempo, we open the a-file. }
13... a5 14. axb4 axb4 15. Be3
{ It is important to finish development before starting to move pawns. } 15...
Nc7 16. c3
{ I think it's best to play in the center and on the kingside at the same time. Thus, we make it difficult for Black to defend. Followed by d4 and g5. }
