[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter guide"]
[Black " 2. ... a6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6
{ This move is often used by players whose main weapon against the Open Sicilian is the Najdorf variation.   3.Nf3  -  d6  4.d4  -  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is a transposition to the main line of Najdorf. The main idea of ​​the move ...a6 is to advance the b-pawn as soon as possible and create pressure on the important e-pawn. }
3. g3
{ As before, we're intending to develop the Bishop on the important diagonal h1-a8. }
3... b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d3
{ We are playing the Closed Sicilian, so we're closing the game with d3. White could continue either with Nge2 or open the game with d4. }
5... e6 6. Nh3
{ Quite rare, but a very interesting move. The main idea is to keep the d1-h5 diagonal open for the Queen on d1. In addition, White has better control over the d5-square and has the opportunity to transfer the Knight to f4 or g5. I think this variation is a great finding for the Closed Sicilian player. }
6... Nf6 { The most popular and logical move. } 7. O-O
{ White already has a concrete threat - to play e5. } 7... d6 8. f4
{ In addition to the concrete tactical threat e5, which is not so difficult to defend against, white's key idea is to advance the f-pawn. I believe that this position is a tabia of this variation. Black has a lot of different continuations to choose from. }
8... Nc6
{ The most logical of all possible moves, and therefore the most popular. Though I have to admit, this logical sequence doesn't always work. }
9. f5 { Putting strong pressure on the e6-pawn. } 9... b4
{ The most principled move. } 10. fxe6
{ If we simply retreat with the Knight, then Black will close the game by e5 and we will no longer have the opportunity to play Nd5, as in the variation above. Therefore, we're choosing the sharpest continuation - the piece sacrifice! }
10... bxc3 11. exf7+ Kxf7 12. bxc3
{ IWhat can you expect having only two pawns for a sacrificed piece? But we just have huge compensation. The Black King is terribly weak, half of the Black pieces is undeveloped and the other half, which is already developed, is awfully coordinated. }
12... Ra7
{ An attempt to involve the Rook to the defense through the seventh rank. } 13.
Rb1
{ At first, we're improving the position of the pieces on all sides as much as possible. }
13... Ba8 14. Ng5+ { It's time to start the attack! } 14... Kg8 15. Bh3
{ Not the most obvious, but amazing move. We're unexpectedly involving the Bishop in the attack, transferring it to the a2-g8 diagonal. This idea was the only reason the sacrifice of the piece was possible. }
15... Re7 16. d4
{ Black can't still defend against Be6, so there is no need to rush. } 16... h6
17. Be6+ { And now it's time to take the material back. } 17... Rxe6 18. Nxe6
Qe7 19. d5
{ White has not only a slight material advantage but also a total positional domination. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6...e6,  early Rb8"]
[Black "#1 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 early ...Rb8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Robert James Fisher believed that it's possible to get an advantage only after 1.e4. Many years have passed since then, chess has made 180 degree-change with the advent of the computer, but it seems to me that old Fischer was right after all. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense! It's one of the most ambitious and exciting chess openings. The Sicilian Defense is the main weapon in the hands of such personalities as Kasparov and Fisher. A little lateral move, but in this way Black prevents the move d2-d4, which you would like to do if you had the opportunity to make two moves in a row. And I’m sure, dear readers, that if you with the first move start the game with a royal pawn, you will meet this position on the board more often than going to a supermarket. The main move in this position is 2. Nf3, which leads to an open variation of the Sicilian Defense. And of course, a Sicilian player wants to impose a complicated, sharp position in which there are a huge number of theoretical variations. A Sicilian player, like a predator plant Venus flytrap, attracts you with its bright lining, but as soon as you get inside, the trap immediately closes. }
2. Nc3
{ The Closed Sicilian Defense! White develops the Queen's Knight instead of the King's one, refusing to advance d2-d4, which is the main plan in the open Sicilian Defense. But on the other hand, White’s position on the kingside is more flexible, and we still have the option of moving the pawn to f4, which we will gladly use in future lines. }
2... Nc6
{ Black's most popular continuation. The most principled move, Black immediately develops the knight and takes control of the d4-square. }
3. g3
{ Since playing d2-d4 is no longer possible in the near future, we will inevitably have to play d2-d3. This means that we should develop the light-squared Bishop on g2, that is, we need to fianchetto the Bishop. }
3... g6
{ Black follows the same strategy! The fianchettoed Bishop on g7 will be perfectly located on the open diagonal a1-h8. An open diagonal is a strategic element in chess, that is no less important than an open file. Like a Rook, a Bishop likes to be in open space and shoot all over the board. Moreover, playing d4 for White will be much more difficult in the future. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 { Obvious solutions that logically continue the previous moves. } 5.
d3
{ Our light-squared Bishop is already well-settled in the game, so we can place a pawn on the light square without a shadow of a doubt. The main idea of ​​this move is, of course, to open the way to the dark-squared Bishop. }
5... d6
{ Black also opens the way for the light-squared Bishop, simultaneously defending the c5-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ The only good square for the Bishop - it does not interfere with the advancement of the f-pawn and the Queen development on d2. }
6... e6
{ Black has two main systems - the first, the most popular, is to develop the Knight on e7, freeing this square with the move e7-e6. The Knight on e7 looks rather passive, but the main idea of ​​this plan is to leave the a1-h8 diagonal open and place the Knight on d4 to interfere with the advancement of the pawn on d4. Useful advice - if there is no Knight on d4, White can break through with d2-d4, then the pawn on d6 will be an obvious weakness.   6. ...Nf6  The second system is the immediate development of the Knight on f6. It has the right to life, but the main drawback of this concept is that Black’s fianchettoed Bishop is now blocked, and to put the Knight on d4, Black will have to spend the tempo on the Knight's move sooner or later. }
7. Qd2
{ The best plan to fight a strong fianchettoed Bishop is to destroy it! Or at least to trade it :@@EndBracket@@ As we can see, black pawns on the kingside are placed on light squares. This means that the black Bishop is the only piece that protects the potentially weak dark squares. And after exchanging dark-squared Bishops, potentially weak squares become simply weak! By Qd2 we aim at the square h6. }
7... Rb8
{ Now Black has a large number of different continuations, which, however, quite often transpose into each other, but we will focus on the most popular choice of Rb8. In the Closed Sicilian Defense, White creates most often an attack on the kingside, while Blacks, in turn, attempt to break through White’s defense on the queenside. Pawn's pushing is one of the most common attack plans. ...Rb8 is played to support the advancement of b5 and b4. In turn, White often plays f4-f5. }
8. Nge2
{ We're not only developing the last undeveloped piece but also creating a dangerous threat d3-d4, which must be considered by Black.   8.Nf3!?  I don't recommend using this move as the main one in classic games, but this is a great option for blitz and rapid ones. In over 300 games, Nd4 was automatically played, which is a blunder!  8. ...Nd4?  Most popular but just a bad move!   8. ...b5!  The strongest move that indirectly prevents d4. If ...b5 is played with you after all, then this is not a reason to despair!  9.O-O   9.d4?  Nf6  10.dxc5  b4!  11.Ne2  Nxe4  12.Qd1  Nxc5  Black has an extra pawn and initiative.  9. ...b4  10.Nd1  Yes, White has no advantage, but there is solid equality.  9.Bxd4  cxd4  10.Nb5!  Qb6   10. ...e5  The straightforward pawn defense  11.Qb4!  The important intermediate move, ensuring a safe retreat of the Knight after taking a pawn on a7.  11. ...Bf8  12.Nxa7  White has a healthy extra pawn.  11.Qb4  Ke7  12.e5  If we imagine the same position, but with a Knight on f3, we'll find that e5 would be simply impossible because of ...Bxe5. This is the idea of the move 8. Nf3! }
8... Nd4
{ An important move! Black centralizes the Knight, and most importantly, prevents the planned advance of d3-d4. But on the other hand, black loses an important tempo, because one of the rules for playing the opening is to not move one piece twice or more if the rest of the pieces are still not developed. }
9. O-O
{ There are three general guidelines valid for any opening: fight for the center, develop all pieces, and hide the King. Castling queenside seems like a logical step because we are going to create an attack on the kingside. But still, it is too dangerous - the black infantrymen are already determined to go on the attack.   9.Bxd4  It is no longer possible to win a pawn with this move because the Knight on e2 is too passive and does not support the advance e4-e5.  9. ...cxd4  10.Nb5  Qb6  11.Qb4  Ke7  Here e5 simply loses a pawn after ...Bxe5. Black is much better. }
9... Ne7
{ Black is trying to finish the development of the pieces, but Black is still two tempos behind - the light-squared Bishop isn’t developed, the King hasn't castled yet. }
10. Bh6
{ The idea that we planned a few moves back comes true! We exchange dark-squared Bishops, to weaken the dark squares, and to remove an important defender of the Black King. The idea of ​​exchanging a fianchettoed Bishop is typical, so you can use this motif in a variety of openings. Besides, Bh6 is our first pawn sacrifice! }
10... O-O 11. Bxg7 { We bring our plan to life. } 11... Kxg7 12. f4
{ A fresh idea in the old variation! That is why we play the Closed Sicilian Defense. A clear plan of attack on the king without many stacks of theoretical variations. We push the pawn to f4, waiting for a convenient moment to break through Black's defense with f5. }
12... b5
{ It seems to me that this particular move is the most critical. Black starts an attack on the queenside. Who will be the first in this race? }
13. Nd1
{ At first glance, an extremely passive and illogical move. After all, you need to keep the Knight in the center, right? What are the basic principles of an attack? First of all, you need to move the maximum number of pieces closer to the enemy King. Secondly, you need to expose the opponent king. By Nc3-Nd1, we transfer the knight to the e3 square, where the knight will be on the kingside and support the advance of f4-f5. Moreover, we have the option to kick the strong d4 Knight out with c2-c3. }
13... Bb7 { Black finally finishes the development of minor pieces. } 14. Ne3
{ A logical continuation of our plan, but at the same time a novelty! } 14...
d5 { And Black is the first, who violates the 'truce' between the parties! }
15. Nxd4
{ We exchange the unpleasant Knight and begin an attack on the kingside. }
15... cxd4 16. Ng4 { The Knight on the kingside upsets Black’s peace. } 16...
h5 17. f5
{ We open the way for the Queen and threaten the fork f6 as well. Black cannot defend against two threats at the same time. }
17... hxg4
{ Careless capture of the pawn on f5 leads to a forced checkmate.   17. ...gxf5?  18.Qh6+  Kg8  19.Nf6# }
18. f6+ { A fork! } 18... Kh7
{ The only way! Otherwise, the white Queen will get on the h6 square. } 19.
fxe7 Qxe7 20. e5
{ Black has two pairs of doubled pawns and the slightly opened King. White’s position is clearly preferable. }
*

