{ Since playing d2-d4 is no longer possible in the near future, we will inevitably have to play d2-d3. This means that we should develop the light-squared Bishop on g2, that is, we need to fianchetto the Bishop. }
3... g6
{ Black follows the same strategy! The fianchettoed Bishop on g7 will be perfectly located on the open diagonal a1-h8. An open diagonal is a strategic element in chess, that is no less important than an open file. Like a Rook, a Bishop likes to be in open space and shoot all over the board. Moreover, playing d4 for White will be much more difficult in the future. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 { Obvious solutions that logically continue the previous moves. } 5.
d3
{ Our light-squared Bishop is already well-settled in the game, so we can place a pawn on the light square without a shadow of a doubt. The main idea of ​​this move is, of course, to open the way to the dark-squared Bishop. }
5... d6
{ Black also opens the way for the light-squared Bishop, simultaneously defending the c5-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ The only good square for the Bishop - it does not interfere with the advancement of the f-pawn and the Queen development on d2. }
6... e6
{ Black has two main systems - the first, the most popular, is to develop the Knight on e7, freeing this square with the move e7-e6. The Knight on e7 looks rather passive, but the main idea of ​​this plan is to leave the a1-h8 diagonal open and place the Knight on d4 to interfere with the advancement of the pawn on d4. Useful advice - if there is no Knight on d4, White can break through with d2-d4, then the pawn on d6 will be an obvious weakness.   6. ...Nf6  The second system is the immediate development of the Knight on f6. It has the right to life, but the main drawback of this concept is that Black’s fianchettoed Bishop is now blocked, and to put the Knight on d4, Black will have to spend the tempo on the Knight's move sooner or later. }
7. Qd2
{ The best plan to fight a strong fianchettoed Bishop is to destroy it! Or at least to trade it :@@EndBracket@@ As we can see, black pawns on the kingside are placed on light squares. This means that the black Bishop is the only piece that protects the potentially weak dark squares. And after exchanging dark-squared Bishops, potentially weak squares become simply weak! By Qd2 we aim at the square h6. }
7... Rb8
{ Now Black has a large number of different continuations, which, however, quite often transpose into each other, but we will focus on the most popular choice of Rb8. In the Closed Sicilian Defense, White creates most often an attack on the kingside, while Blacks, in turn, attempt to break through White’s defense on the queenside. Pawn's pushing is one of the most common attack plans. ...Rb8 is played to support the advancement of b5 and b4. In turn, White often plays f4-f5. }
8. Nge2
{ We're not only developing the last undeveloped piece but also creating a dangerous threat d3-d4, which must be considered by Black.   8.Nf3!?  I don't recommend using this move as the main one in classic games, but this is a great option for blitz and rapid ones. In over 300 games, Nd4 was automatically played, which is a blunder!  8. ...Nd4?  Most popular but just a bad move!   8. ...b5!  The strongest move that indirectly prevents d4. If ...b5 is played with you after all, then this is not a reason to despair!  9.O-O   9.d4?  Nf6  10.dxc5  b4!  11.Ne2  Nxe4  12.Qd1  Nxc5  Black has an extra pawn and initiative.  9. ...b4  10.Nd1  Yes, White has no advantage, but there is solid equality.  9.Bxd4  cxd4  10.Nb5!  Qb6   10. ...e5  The straightforward pawn defense  11.Qb4!  The important intermediate move, ensuring a safe retreat of the Knight after taking a pawn on a7.  11. ...Bf8  12.Nxa7  White has a healthy extra pawn.  11.Qb4  Ke7  12.e5  If we imagine the same position, but with a Knight on f3, we'll find that e5 would be simply impossible because of ...Bxe5. This is the idea of the move 8. Nf3! }
8... Nd4
{ An important move! Black centralizes the Knight, and most importantly, prevents the planned advance of d3-d4. But on the other hand, black loses an important tempo, because one of the rules for playing the opening is to not move one piece twice or more if the rest of the pieces are still not developed. }
9. O-O
{ There are three general guidelines valid for any opening: fight for the center, develop all pieces, and hide the King. Castling queenside seems like a logical step because we are going to create an attack on the kingside. But still, it is too dangerous - the black infantrymen are already determined to go on the attack.   9.Bxd4  It is no longer possible to win a pawn with this move because the Knight on e2 is too passive and does not support the advance e4-e5.  9. ...cxd4  10.Nb5  Qb6  11.Qb4  Ke7  Here e5 simply loses a pawn after ...Bxe5. Black is much better. }
9... Ne7
{ Black is trying to finish the development of the pieces, but Black is still two tempos behind - the light-squared Bishop isn’t developed, the King hasn't castled yet. }
10. Bh6
{ The idea that we planned a few moves back comes true! We exchange dark-squared Bishops, to weaken the dark squares, and to remove an important defender of the Black King. The idea of ​​exchanging a fianchettoed Bishop is typical, so you can use this motif in a variety of openings. Besides, Bh6 is our first pawn sacrifice! }
10... O-O 11. Bxg7 { We bring our plan to life. } 11... Kxg7 12. f4
{ A fresh idea in the old variation! That is why we play the Closed Sicilian Defense. A clear plan of attack on the king without many stacks of theoretical variations. We push the pawn to f4, waiting for a convenient moment to break through Black's defense with f5. }
12... Qa5 13. g4
{ I suggest you start a pawn storm on the Black fortress, which forces our opponent to play extremely accurately. }
13... f5 { The only way to prevent our pawn breakthrough. } 14. gxf5 exf5 15.
a3
{ We slightly change our usual plan of action and create play on the queenside. My main opening for Black vs. 1. d4 is the King's Indian Defense. And in the King's Indian Defense, just like in the Closed Sicilian Defense, each side conducts an attack, mainly on its side. But I always admired the ability of some players, for example, Hikaru Nakamura, to start playing at the right time not on his field, but on the side, where it is assumed that the opponent is stronger. }
15... Bd7 16. Rab1 { Preparing b2-b4 } 16... b5 17. b4
{ Temporarily sacrificing a pawn. } 17... Qxa3 18. Nxd4 cxd4 19. Ne2
{ And Black has no good way to protect the d4 pawn. } 19... Nc6
{ The move that perfectly illustrates White’s idea. } 20. exf5 gxf5 21. Bxc6
{ Destroying the piece that attacks our pawn. } 21... Bxc6 22. Ra1
{ And the Queen is trapped! } *

