10... Nxe2+ 11. Nxe2 Bxb2
{ You need to be a big optimist to decide to accept the pawn sacrifice! The Black's King cannot be castled due to the Bishop on h6, Black's pieces are still poorly developed. At the same time, our pieces are harmoniously placed, and the pawn on d6 will be won back sooner or later. For example, }
12. Rab1 Bf6 13. d4
{ We need to justify the pawn sacrifice, thus we break through the center. }
13... cxd4 14. Nxd4 Bd7 15. Rfd1 { Placing one more piece on the open d-file. }
15... Qc7 16. h4 { Grabbing some space on the kingside. } 16... a6 17. Nf3 Bb5
18. Qxd6 Qxd6 19. Rxd6
{ White's pieces are better coordinated, and the Black King is stuck in the center. White has a big advantage. }
