10... Bxh6
{ Just a mistake that allows White to have an excellent Queen in the Black camp. Perhaps, dear readers, you have heard one more opening rule. Do not develop the Queen too early at the beginning of the game. But the Queen located in the center of the battlefield is bad only when it can be attacked by the opponent’s pieces. In this case, our Queen prevents Black from castling and is almost invulnerable. }
11. Qxh6 Ng8
{ Why is it almost invulnerable? The Queen can still be attacked by the Knight, which allows Black not to lose the game right away, but honestly, how many of us are ready to make such an ugly move?   11. ...Nxc2?  is an important move.  12.Rac1  Nd4   12. ...Nb4  is a better try  13.Qg7  Rg8  14.Qxh7  Nxd3  15.Rcd1  Nxb2  16.e5!  attacking the d6-pawn and intending to play Ne4  16. ...Nxd1  17.Rxd1  d5  18.Ne4!  White is going to play Nf6. Compensation is huge.  13.Nxd4  cxd4  14.Nb5  Threatening to play Nc7 and Nxd4  14. ...Nc6  15.Qg7  Ke7  16.Nxd4  White is much better due to the bad Black King. }
12. Qd2
{ The easiest way is to move the Queen back and get a comfortable advantage in development. }
12... Nxe2+ 13. Nxe2 Nf6 14. Rad1
{ Black dark squares are weak. White has a clear play connected with advancement d- or f-pawn. }
