{ We're not only developing the last undeveloped piece but also creating a dangerous threat d3-d4, which must be considered by Black.   8.Nf3!?  I don't recommend using this move as the main one in classic games, but this is a great option for blitz and rapid ones. In over 300 games, Nd4 was automatically played, which is a blunder!  8. ...Nd4?  Most popular but just a bad move!   8. ...b5!  The strongest move that indirectly prevents d4. If ...b5 is played with you after all, then this is not a reason to despair!  9.O-O   9.d4?  Nf6  10.dxc5  b4!  11.Ne2  Nxe4  12.Qd1  Nxc5  Black has an extra pawn and initiative.  9. ...b4  10.Nd1  Yes, White has no advantage, but there is solid equality.  9.Bxd4  cxd4  10.Nb5!  Qb6   10. ...e5  The straightforward pawn defense  11.Qb4!  The important intermediate move, ensuring a safe retreat of the Knight after taking a pawn on a7.  11. ...Bf8  12.Nxa7  White has a healthy extra pawn.  11.Qb4  Ke7  12.e5  If we imagine the same position, but with a Knight on f3, we'll find that e5 would be simply impossible because of ...Bxe5. This is the idea of the move 8. Nf3! }
8... b5
{ The second most popular move. Black immediately begins an attack on the queenside. Although starting to push pawns is not the best idea, while minor pieces are not developed and the King is not castled. }
9. O-O b4 { The main move. Black focuses his play on the queenside. } 10. Nd1
Nd4 11. Nc1
{ And again, I recommend this move. The more pieces are on the board, the greater is the tension! }
11... Ne7 12. c3 { Kicking out the Knight! } 12... bxc3 13. bxc3 Ndc6 14. Bh6
O-O 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Ne3 { Standard transfer of the Knight to the center. }
16... f5
{ A bit of a weird decision. After all, White has not played f4 yet, and Black is already preventing f5! Just a weakening the pawn structure. }
17. Ne2 Qc7 18. exf5 Nxf5 19. Nxf5+ Rxf5 20. Nf4
{ And again Black has the bad King and the weak e6-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6...e6,  early Rb8"]
[Black "#17 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 early ...Rb8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Robert James Fisher believed that it's possible to get an advantage only after 1.e4. Many years have passed since then, chess has made 180 degree-change with the advent of the computer, but it seems to me that old Fischer was right after all. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense! It's one of the most ambitious and exciting chess openings. The Sicilian Defense is the main weapon in the hands of such personalities as Kasparov and Fisher. A little lateral move, but in this way Black prevents the move d2-d4, which you would like to do if you had the opportunity to make two moves in a row. And I’m sure, dear readers, that if you with the first move start the game with a royal pawn, you will meet this position on the board more often than going to a supermarket. The main move in this position is 2. Nf3, which leads to an open variation of the Sicilian Defense. And of course, a Sicilian player wants to impose a complicated, sharp position in which there are a huge number of theoretical variations. A Sicilian player, like a predator plant Venus flytrap, attracts you with its bright lining, but as soon as you get inside, the trap immediately closes. }
2. Nc3
{ The Closed Sicilian Defense! White develops the Queen's Knight instead of the King's one, refusing to advance d2-d4, which is the main plan in the open Sicilian Defense. But on the other hand, White’s position on the kingside is more flexible, and we still have the option of moving the pawn to f4, which we will gladly use in future lines. }
2... Nc6
{ Black's most popular continuation. The most principled move, Black immediately develops the knight and takes control of the d4-square. }
3. g3
{ Since playing d2-d4 is no longer possible in the near future, we will inevitably have to play d2-d3. This means that we should develop the light-squared Bishop on g2, that is, we need to fianchetto the Bishop. }
3... g6
{ Black follows the same strategy! The fianchettoed Bishop on g7 will be perfectly located on the open diagonal a1-h8. An open diagonal is a strategic element in chess, that is no less important than an open file. Like a Rook, a Bishop likes to be in open space and shoot all over the board. Moreover, playing d4 for White will be much more difficult in the future. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 { Obvious solutions that logically continue the previous moves. } 5.
d3
{ Our light-squared Bishop is already well-settled in the game, so we can place a pawn on the light square without a shadow of a doubt. The main idea of ​​this move is, of course, to open the way to the dark-squared Bishop. }
5... d6
{ Black also opens the way for the light-squared Bishop, simultaneously defending the c5-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ The only good square for the Bishop - it does not interfere with the advancement of the f-pawn and the Queen development on d2. }
6... e6
{ Black has two main concepts - the first, the most popular, is to develop the Knight on e7, freeing this square with the move e7-e6. The knight on e7 looks rather passive, but the main idea of ​​this plan is to leave the a1-h8 diagonal open and place the knight on d4 to interfere with the advancement of the pawn on d4. Useful advice - if there is no knight on d4, White can break through with d2-d4, then the pawn on d6 will be an obvious weakness. }
7. Qd2
{ The best plan to fight a strong fianchettoed Bishop is to destroy it! Or at least to trade it :@@EndBracket@@ As we can see, black pawns on the kingside are placed on light squares. This means that the black Bishop is the only piece that protects the potentially weak dark squares. And after exchanging dark-squared Bishops, potentially weak squares become simply weak! By Qd2 we aim at the square h6. }
7... Rb8
{ Now Black has a large number of different continuations, which, however, quite often transpose into each other, but we will focus on the most popular choice of Rb8. In the Closed Sicilian Defense, White creates most often an attack on the kingside, while Blacks, in turn, attempt to break through White’s defense on the queenside. Pawn's pushing is one of the most common attack plans. ...Rb8 is played to support the advancement of b5 and b4. In turn, White often plays f4-f5. }
8. Nge2
{ We're not only developing the last undeveloped piece but also creating a dangerous threat d3-d4, which must be considered by Black.   8.Nf3!?  I don't recommend using this move as the main one in classic games, but this is a great option for blitz and rapid ones. In over 300 games, Nd4 was automatically played, which is a blunder!  8. ...Nd4?  Most popular but just a bad move!   8. ...b5!  The strongest move that indirectly prevents d4. If ...b5 is played with you after all, then this is not a reason to despair!  9.O-O   9.d4?  Nf6  10.dxc5  b4!  11.Ne2  Nxe4  12.Qd1  Nxc5  Black has an extra pawn and initiative.  9. ...b4  10.Nd1  Yes, White has no advantage, but there is solid equality.  9.Bxd4  cxd4  10.Nb5!  Qb6   10. ...e5  The straightforward pawn defense  11.Qb4!  The important intermediate move, ensuring a safe retreat of the Knight after taking a pawn on a7.  11. ...Bf8  12.Nxa7  White has a healthy extra pawn.  11.Qb4  Ke7  12.e5  If we imagine the same position, but with a Knight on f3, we'll find that e5 would be simply impossible because of ...Bxe5. This is the idea of the move 8. Nf3! }
8... b5
{ The second most popular move. Black immediately begins an attack on the queenside. Although starting to push pawns is not the best idea, while minor pieces are not developed and the King is not castled. }
9. O-O Nd4
{ Black is very active on the queenside and in the center, but the kingside is still undeveloped. }
10. Nd1
{ A standard move. We free the c3-square for the pawn and transfer the Knight to e3. }
10... Ne7
{ Of course, it was possible to kick the Knight out with c3 immediately. But I recommend keeping as many pieces on the board as possible and kicking the Knight on d4 out with a tempo. }
11. Nc1 O-O 12. c3 Ndc6 13. Bh6
{ Do not forget to exchange a strong black dark-squared Bishop! } 13... d5 14.
Bxg7 Kxg7 15. exd5 exd5 16. Nb3 Qd6 17. d4 c4 18. Nc5
{ And White occupies a perfect c5 square with his Knight, which gives him a big advantage. }
*

