[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6...e6,  early Rb8"]
[Black "#33 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 early ...Rb8"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4
{ Robert James Fisher believed that it's possible to get an advantage only after 1.e4. Many years have passed since then, chess has made 180 degree-change with the advent of the computer, but it seems to me that old Fischer was right after all. }
1... c5
{ The Sicilian Defense! It's one of the most ambitious and exciting chess openings. The Sicilian Defense is the main weapon in the hands of such personalities as Kasparov and Fisher. A little lateral move, but in this way Black prevents the move d2-d4, which you would like to do if you had the opportunity to make two moves in a row. And I’m sure, dear readers, that if you with the first move start the game with a royal pawn, you will meet this position on the board more often than going to a supermarket. The main move in this position is 2. Nf3, which leads to an open variation of the Sicilian Defense. And of course, a Sicilian player wants to impose a complicated, sharp position in which there are a huge number of theoretical variations. A Sicilian player, like a predator plant Venus flytrap, attracts you with its bright lining, but as soon as you get inside, the trap immediately closes. }
2. Nc3
{ The Closed Sicilian Defense! White develops the Queen's Knight instead of the King's one, refusing to advance d2-d4, which is the main plan in the open Sicilian Defense. But on the other hand, White’s position on the kingside is more flexible, and we still have the option of moving the pawn to f4, which we will gladly use in future lines. }
2... Nc6
{ Black's most popular continuation. The most principled move, Black immediately develops the knight and takes control of the d4-square. }
3. g3
{ Since playing d2-d4 is no longer possible in the near future, we will inevitably have to play d2-d3. This means that we should develop the light-squared Bishop on g2, that is, we need to fianchetto the Bishop. }
3... g6
{ Black follows the same strategy! The fianchettoed Bishop on g7 will be perfectly located on the open diagonal a1-h8. An open diagonal is a strategic element in chess, that is no less important than an open file. Like a Rook, a Bishop likes to be in open space and shoot all over the board. Moreover, playing d4 for White will be much more difficult in the future. }
4. Bg2 Bg7 { Obvious solutions that logically continue the previous moves. } 5.
d3
{ Our light-squared Bishop is already well-settled in the game, so we can place a pawn on the light square without a shadow of a doubt. The main idea of ​​this move is, of course, to open the way to the dark-squared Bishop. }
5... d6
{ Black also opens the way for the light-squared Bishop, simultaneously defending the c5-pawn. }
6. Be3
{ The only good square for the Bishop - it does not interfere with the advancement of the f-pawn and the Queen development on d2. }
6... Rb8
{ Black has a large number of alternatives, but we will concentrate only on this move since in this chapter we will analyze mainly early ... Rb8 followed by ... b5 }
7. Qd2 { Developing the Queen with the idea to exchange dark-squared Bishops. }
7... b5
{ The idea of early ...Rb8 is early ...b5! On the one hand, Black immediately asks White some questions on the queenside. On the other hand, Black's kingside is completely undeveloped, which can lead to unpleasant consequences. }
8. Nge2
{ Developing the Knight on e2, leaving the possibility to push the f pawn and aiming at the advancement d4 in some variations. }
8... b4
{ Only this move has an independent value! Black continues the early attack on the queenside. }
9. Nd1 { We should not forget about b2 pawn! } 9... Qb6
{ Black is preparing to open the b-file } 10. O-O e6 11. a3
{ I always admire people who can play on both sides of the board simultaneously. Before starting the standard plan on the kingside, we open the a-file. }
11... a5 12. axb4 axb4
{ The Rook did not make a single move but has already become active. Isn't it amazing? }
13. c3 bxc3 14. bxc3 Ba6 15. f4 { Starting our standard plan. } 15... Nge7 16.
g4 { Preparing to play f5. } 16... f5 17. gxf5 exf5 18. Ng3
{ Black's King is stuck in the center. } 18... O-O
{ If Black inaccurately plays O-O, then the unexpected Qa2 wins the piece. }
19. Qa2+ *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6: 5...d6, 6...e6, 7...Nge7"]
[Black "#1 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 7. ... Nge7"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 Nge7
{ In the previous chapter, we discussed the early ...Rb8 move. The equally popular move ...Nge7 is the most logical and natural move in this position from the point of view of simple chess understanding. Black develops a minor piece and prepares to make a kingside castle. What could be the drawback of this move? }
8. Bh6
{ The h6 square becomes unprotected, so we are very happy to exchange the strong fianchettoed Bishop on g7. Black's kingside pawns are located on light squares, which means that exchanging the dark-squared Bishops is definitely beneficial for White. }
8... O-O
{ The most popular and simplest solution, although dangerous. White's cannons are already loaded, and the Black King voluntarily goes into the thick of the battle. }
9. h4
{ We start the attack as soon as possible. This is a standard attack plan against such a kingside pawn structure. In a military battle, it is important to use all the guns, and in a chess game, all the pieces. With the h4-move, we want to push the pawn even further and open the h-file, thus involving the Rook into play. }
9... f6
{ The strongest move! Black prepares ...g5, preventing the opening of the h-file. }
10. Bxg7 { Exchanging the main defender of the Black fortress. } 10... Kxg7 11.
h5
{ Although opening the h-file will most likely fail, it is important to provoke Black to advance the pawns on the kingside, which makes the King's position weak. }
11... g5 12. h6+
{ Black wanted to play ...h6, creating a fairly strong pawn chain that would not be easy to break. Therefore, we must disrupt the coordination of Black pieces and make the pawn on g5 more vulnerable. }
12... Kh8 { The safest square for the King at the moment. } 13. f4
{ The g5 pawn has been advanced unforgivably far, so we don't miss a chance to attack it and open the kingside. }
13... gxf4 { The most natural move. } 14. gxf4
{ Of course, we take with a pawn without disturbing the harmony of our pawn structure. }
14... Rb8
{ I think this is Black's most principled move. Black is preparing the b5 advance, the most common plan in the Closed Sicilian. }
15. Nf3
{ After the pawn is already on f4, it's a good idea to develop the Knight to f3. 'Pawns in front, pieces to the rear' as Philidor wrote. }
15... b5 { Black starts his attack on the queenside. } 16. e5
{ Attack of the most defended square! We want to open the position even further, while simultaneously destroying Black's pawn structure. }
16... dxe5
{ In my opinion, the capture by the d-pawn is a little safer, since Black leaves one pawn on the kingside. }
17. fxe5 f5 18. O-O-O
{ Before starting active actions on the kingside, we need to secure our own King. }
18... Ng6 19. Ne2
{ We are transferring the Knight to the kingside and preparing the transfer of the Queen to the c3-square in case of the capture of the e5-pawn. }
19... b4 20. d4
{ An unexpected breakthrough in the center! The pawn on e5 is now protected, and in case of a capture, we will control the d-file. }
20... c4 21. Qg5 { Offering to exchange Queens. } 21... Bb7 22. Rhg1
{ Occupying the open g-file. The endgame will be more favorable for White due to more active pieces, more space in the center and on the kingside, and a weak pawn on e6. }
*

