{ The most popular and simplest solution, although dangerous. White's cannons are already loaded, and the Black King voluntarily goes into the thick of the battle. }
9. h4
{ We start the attack as soon as possible. This is a standard attack plan against such a kingside pawn structure. In a military battle, it is important to use all the guns, and in a chess game, all the pieces. With the h4-move, we want to push the pawn even further and open the h-file, thus involving the Rook into play. }
9... Bxh6
{ I would not play this move in a game, because Black is simply helping White's Queen to participate in the attack. }
10. Qxh6 Kh8
{ The idea behind this move is to kick the Queen out with ...Ng8, but Black's pieces will be too passive. }
11. h5
{ Don't refuse a gift! If it is possible to play h5 painlessly, play h5! }
11... Ng8 12. Qd2 { The safest square for the Queen. } 12... Nd4
{ What if Black centralizes the Knight immediately? } 13. hxg6
{ Opening the h file } 13... fxg6 14. e5
{ Grabbing the space in the center and breaking Black's pawn chain. } 14... d5
15. Nce2 { It's important to exchange the opponent's strong pieces. } 15...
Nxe2 16. Nxe2
{ And White is much better due to excellent pieces, especially the Rook on h1, and the exposed Black King. }
