[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6...e6, 7...Nd4"]
[Black "#1 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 7. ... Nd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 Nd4
{ 'Don't move the same piece twice.' - one of the fundamental opening principles. Nevertheless, we should not think dogmatically, not accept certain rules without argument, but make a decision based on the concrete situation. This is one of the thoughts that I have successfully applied in my life, by the way. Black ignored this principle already on the seventh move, but is it really that bad? I think not, since now White can't play Bh6, as in variation 7. ... Nge7. }
8. Nd1
{ It's time for plan B! We are waiting for the opportunity to play Bh6, wanting to attack the Knight at the same time. }
8... Ne7 { Black has to finish the development anyway! } 9. c3
{ Of course, we can't play   9.Bh6  now because of  9....Bxh6  10.Qxh6  and  10....Nxc2!  Therefore, we first drive the Knight from the central position. }
9... Ndc6 10. Bh6
{ The pawn on c3 is no longer under attack, the Knight is already on the e7 square, so it's time to start our main plan. }
10... O-O 11. h4
{ We had a similar position in chapter 7. ... Nge7, with the difference that the Knight was on c3 and the pawn was on c2. Which version is better? Although it seems that the Knight is passive due to its position on the first rank, we often transfer the knight to e3 anyway, so this is more a plus than a minus. Moreover, the c3-pawn prepares the capture of the center by d4. }
11... f6 { With the idea to ​​close the kingside with ...g5 after h5. } 12.
Bxg7 { So far we should play the same as in chapter 7. ... Nge7. } 12... Kxg7
13. h5 g5 14. Ne2
{ In the position with the Knight on c3, I recommended playing h6 in order to grab even more space on the kingside and prevent ...h6. In general, there is nothing wrong with playing h6 now, but I decided to diversify White's play and show another possible plan. }
14... h6 15. Ne3
{ Developing the Knight to the active position and preparing a queenside castling. }
15... Rb8 16. f4
{ Although our main plan will be connected with the play in the center, it is useful to increase the pressure on the kingside, namely the g5 pawn. }
16... Bd7 17. d4
{ It's time to reap the fruits of our early c3 and Nd1. All of our pieces are in place and ready for a breakthrough in the center. }
17... cxd4 18. Nxd4
{ Of course, we take a pawn with the Knight to open the d-file. } 18... Qb6 19.
O-O-O
{ The development of the pieces is completely over, so we can already evaluate the position. The d-file is open, and it is very difficult for Black to defend the weak d6-pawn. Moreover, Black's kingside pawns are far advanced, while Black's King is just awful. White has excellent chances to both win the weak d-pawn and create a dangerous attack on the kingside. }
