[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6...e6, 7... other"]
[Black "#1 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 7. ... Sidelines"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 Qa5
{ In this chapter, I would like to consider not the most popular, but possible moves.It seems to me that it's the most logical move among the unpopular ones. Black plays in the spirit of the Closed Sicilian: he transfers the Queen to the queenside, thereby increasing the pressure on the c3 Knight and preparing b5. }
8. Nge2
{ We provide more support to the c3 Knight and fight for the control of the d4 square. }
8... Nd4 { A typical move that creates tension in the center. } 9. O-O Ne7 10.
Nxd4
{ I think the best thing to do is to force the transition to the endgame. }
10... cxd4 { Although this is a fork, Black will not be able to win anything. }
11. Ne2
{ We're getting the Knight out of the fork and attacking the Queen at the same time, thereby saving the piece. }
11... Qxd2 12. Bxd2 Nc6 { Quite weak, although the most popular move. } 13. b4
{ We're exploiting the poor position of the Knight! Our plans change dramatically in the endgame. Now, instead of attacking on the kingside, we create a pawn storm on the queenside. What caused such a change in plans? Play where you are stronger! We have completely finished development and are ready to support the movement of the pawns with our Rooks. }
13... Bd7 14. a4 { We continue to grab space on the queenside. } 14... Rc8 15.
b5 { Forcing the Black Knight to retreat back. } 15... Nd8 16. Rfc1
{ Black pieces are passive and poorly coordinated, while we have a huge advantage in space on the queenside and after c3 we deprive Black of the last joy - the d4-pawn. }
*

