[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6: 5... d6, 6... Nf6"]
[Black "#1 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... Nf6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6
{ Another system. The development of the Knight on f6 has both pros and cons. On one hand, Black threatens to play ...Ng4 with the idea of ​​exchanging the strong dark-squared Bishop, and in general, the Knight is more active than on e7. But on the other hand, g7 Bishop is now blocked. }
7. h3
{ But still, in general, the plans of the players remain unchanged. Black wants to create an attack on the queenside with b5, while White plans to push the pawns on the kingside, creating a double-edged position. The pawn move h3 is an important prophylactic move that prevents ...Ng4. }
7... O-O
{ The most popular and logical continuation.   7. ...e5  8.Qd2  Nd4  9.Nge2  O-O  10.f4  it transposes to the main line }
8. Qd2
{ As usual, we need to direct our warriors towards the enemy king. We are preparing both castling and the exchange of dark-squared Bishops with Bh6. }
8... Nd4
{ The most active move in the position. Black centralizes his knight.   8. ...Rb8  transposes to 9. Nge2 b5 10. O-O b4 11. Nd1   8. ...Bd7  transposes to  9. Nge2 Rb8 }
9. Nge2
{ It is important to develop the Knight on e2, and not on f3, to leave yourself the opportunity to play f4. }
9... e5
{ On one hand, the d4 Knight is now reliably protected. But on the other hand, Black inevitably weakened his pawn structure and definitively blocked his Bishop. }
10. f4 { Starting the attack on the kingside. } 10... Rb8 11. f5
{ A novelty! At least none of my databases managed to find games in this position. The main idea is to expose the opponent's King and open the f-file. }
11... gxf5 { Of course, the most principled move. } 12. Bg5
{ The pin is an important strategic element that cannot be underestimated. White threatens to increase the pressure on the pinned Knight with Nd5. }
12... h6
{ 12. ...Ne6  transposes to 13. Bh4 fxe4 14. dxe4 h6 15. Nd5   12. ...fxe4  transposes also to the same line 13. dxe4 h6 14. Bh4 }
13. Bh4 { Continuing the pin. } 13... fxe4 14. dxe4
{ Capturing the pawn with the Knight looks more attractive, but it allows Black to attack our bishop with Nf5. }
14... Qa5 15. O-O
{ Now castling is asking to be played, and White is attacking the Knight on f6. }
15... Nh7 16. g4 { Freeing the g3 square for the Knight. } 16... Nxe2+ 17. Qxe2
Ng5 18. Rad1
{ Black's pawn structure is terrible, and especially the pawn on d6. Therefore, we put the rook on the d-file. }
18... Qd8 19. Kh1
{ Black threatened to capture the pawn on h3, so it's important to make a prophylactic move. }
19... Be6 20. Nb5
{ White has an advantage due to the weak d6 pawn   if  20. ...Nxe4  then we have to defend the Bishop on h4 with  21.Qe1  and after  21. ...Ng5  simply  22.Nxd6  White is much better due to the strong Knight on d6. }
*

