{ On one hand, the d4 Knight is now reliably protected. But on the other hand, Black inevitably weakened his pawn structure and definitively blocked his Bishop. }
10. f4 { Starting the attack on the kingside. } 10... Rb8 11. f5
{ A novelty! At least none of my databases managed to find games in this position. The main idea is to expose the opponent's King and open the f-file. }
11... b5
{ Suppose Black decides not to accept the sacrifice, but to start a typical Closed Sicilian attack. }
12. Bg5
{ As we can see, one of the main goals of advancing the pawn to f5 is to free the Bishop's diagonal. }
12... h6 13. Bxf6
{ Bxh6 doesn't work because of ...Bxh6 and ...Nxc2, and Bh4 doesn't work because of ...g5. Therefore in line with our plan to play Bg5, we are left with just taking the Knight, however, this is not bad for us at all. }
13... Bxf6 14. Nd5
{ 'An outpost is a square on the fourth, fifth, sixth, or seventh rank which is protected by a pawn and which cannot be attacked by an opponent's pawn.' The d5 square is a great example of an outpost. It is especially pleasant to occupy an outpost with a Knight. }
14... gxf5 15. Nxd4 { We are happy to exchange the strong d4 Knight. } 15...
cxd4 16. Qxh6
{ In the case of the automatic capture on d4, we can simply win the pawn on h6. }
16... Bg7 17. Qh5 Bb7 18. exf5
{ Black has no compensation for the pawn and White has a promising attack. } *

