1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nf6
{ Another system. The development of the Knight on f6 has both pros and cons. On one hand, Black threatens to play ...Ng4 with the idea of ​​exchanging the strong dark-squared Bishop, and in general, the Knight is more active than on e7. But on the other hand, g7 Bishop is now blocked. }
7. h3
{ But still, in general, the plans of the players remain unchanged. Black wants to create an attack on the queenside with b5, while White plans to push the pawns on the kingside, creating a double-edged position. The pawn move h3 is an important prophylactic move that prevents ...Ng4. }
7... a6 { A passive move. I'd rather play ...Rb8. } 8. Qd2 O-O 9. Nge2 Qc7 10.
O-O
{ A huge plus of the Closed Sicilian is that instead of memorizing a large number of different variations, you need to know several main plans. For instance, such a setup, the Bishop is on e3, the Queen is d2, the Knight is on e2 and the kingside castling, often occurs. }
10... b5 11. f4 { The main plan in this setup is to advance f4 and f5 } 11...
Bb7 12. f5 Rad8 13. g4 { Followed by Bh6. } *

