{ Since the c1-h6 diagonal is already open, it makes sense to create a threat of Bishop exchange as soon as possible. }
9... Nd4 10. Nf3 Qb6
{ Only this move has an independent meaning, otherwise, there will be a transposition to the main line.   10. ...O-O  transposes to 11. O-O }
11. Rb1 { There is no other reasonable way to defend the b2 pawn. } 11... Bh3
{ The unexpected combination! } 12. O-O
{ Of course, you can't take the Bishop   12.Bxh3  because of the fork on f3.  12. ...Nxf3! }
12... Bxg2 13. Qxg2
{ I can't say that this trade was beneficial for Black since the White light-squared Bishop was imprisoned by its own pawns on c2, d3, and e4. Taking by the King is also possible, albeit slightly weaker. It will be a little more dangerous to advance the g-pawn. }
13... O-O 14. g4
{ We start the movement of pawns, preventing ...f5 at the same time. } 14...
Ne6 15. Be3 Rae8 16. Nd2
{ Followed by Followed by either Nc4 or doubling the Rooks on the f-file. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Setups with Nc6:  5... d6, 6... e5"]
[Black "#22 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e5
{ It seems to me that this is the strongest continuation, but fortunately only the fourth most popular. The main idea behind ​​this move is to grab the space in the center and support the move Nd4. At the same time, this move should not be overestimated. The d6 pawn becomes weak and the dark-squared Bishop is at least temporarily blocked. }
7. f4
{ In comparison with other variations, we don't play Qd2 immediately, but first f4, in order to develop the Knight on f3 as soon as possible. }
7... exf4 8. Bxf4
{ The idea of ​​early capture on f4 is very simple: to open the a1-h8 diagonal for the Black dark-squared Bishop. But this decision also has some drawbacks. Firstly, Black trades the central pawn for a side pawn. Secondly, White's dark-squared bishop also becomes more active. And finally, thirdly, the open f-file is more of a plus for White than for Black. }
8... Nge7 9. Qd2
{ Since the c1-h6 diagonal is already open, it makes sense to create a threat of Bishop exchange as soon as possible. }
9... O-O 10. Bh6
{ Since there is no attack on the c2-pawn by the d4 Knight, we are happy to trade the dark-squared Bishops. }
10... Nd4 11. Bxg7 Kxg7 12. Nge2
{ There is no big difference whether to develop the Knight on e2 or f3. } 12...
Nxe2 13. Nxe2 Nc6 14. O-O Be6 15. Nf4
{ After the advance of the c3 and d4 pawns, White will dominate in the center.  Furthermore, the Knight on f4 gives White control over the d5 square. }
*

