[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6... Nd4"]
[Black "#7 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... Nd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nd4
{ A rare move, but it was played by Garry Kasparov during his peak years in the game with Nigel Short, which means it deserves attention. Black's idea is to postpone the development of the kingside and start immediate actions on the queenside. }
7. Qd2 Qa5 8. f4
{ Since White can't play the typical move Bh6 in these positions in the near future, we play f4! An active move that will allow us to develop the Knight to f3. }
8... e6 9. Nf3 Ne7 10. O-O Nec6 11. e5
{ A typical move for the Closed Sicilian and was played by Short against Kasparov. We are trying to take advantage of the weak defense of Black's kingside and open up the position. }
11... d5
{ This move has both advantages and disadvantages. On the plus side, Black didn't allow us to open the center and create a lightning attack. But on the other hand, we have an advantage in space in the center, the Bishop on g7 is completely blocked, and the Knight on d4 is left without the Bishop's defense. }
12. a3
{ It is important for us to remain flexible, so instead of the typical Kingside plan for the Closed Sicilian, we are preparing a b4 advance on the queenside. }
12... Nxf3+
{ White threatens to play b4, so Black must solve the problem with the d4-knight. }
13. Bxf3 O-O 14. b4
{ And now we are playing in the spirit of Benko gambit, sacrificing a pawn to open the a and b-files. }
14... cxb4 15. axb4 Qxb4 16. Rfb1 { Our Rooks look great! } 16... Qe7 17. Qf2
{ Threatening to win an exchange by Bс5. } 17... Re8 18. Bc5
{ In any case, we improve the position of the Bishop. } 18... Qd7 19. Nb5
{ With an unstoppable threat to play Bd6 and Nc7. } *

