[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6:  5...d6, 6... Nd4"]
[Black "#19 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... Nd4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Nd4
{ A rare move, but it was played by Garry Kasparov during his peak years in the game with Nigel Short, which means it deserves attention. Black's idea is to postpone the development of the kingside and start immediate actions on the queenside. }
7. Qd2 Qa5 8. f4
{ Since White can't play the typical move Bh6 in these positions in the near future, we play f4! An active move that will allow us to develop the Knight to f3. }
8... Nf6 9. Nf3 Nxf3+ 10. Bxf3 Bh3
{ Black's attempt to prevent kingside castling. } 11. Nd1
{ So, we are transposing to an endgame where castling will no longer be necessary to us! }
11... Qxd2+ 12. Bxd2
{ We are taking with a Bishop on d2, not with a King because we are going to transfer the Bishop to c3 and we are opening up the e3-square for the Knight. }
12... O-O 13. Bc3
{ Our dark-squared Bishop will be an excellent opponent for the Black Bishop along the a1-h8 diagonal. }
13... Rad8 14. Ne3
{ White's chances are a little bit more preferable due to the slight advantage in space and the better position of the pieces. }
