[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. Nc6: The Smyslov variation"]
[Black "#1 Smyslov variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6
{ Black tries to save the move ...d6 in order to make the move ...d5 without losing a tempo. }
6. Be3
{ Of course, White disrupts this plan, and now the c5-pawn is under attack. The move ...d6 leads to the main variation 5. ...d6. }
6... Nd4
{ Black improves the position of the Knight and defends the c5-pawn at the same time.   6. ...d6  transposes to the main position of the Closed Sicilian }
7. Nce2
{ This is a critical starting position -'tabia'. This move was played by the world champion Vasily Smyslov several times in 1946 and 1947. I think that this variation deserves to be named after Smyslov. We are trying to drive off the strong d4-Knight as quickly as possible. Black has several continuations. }
7... Ne7 8. c3
{ This is the idea behind the move Nce2 - to free the c3 square for the pawn. }
8... Nxe2 9. Nxe2 d6
{ The most natural and popular way to defend the c5-pawn. } 10. Qd2
{ There was nothing wrong with playing d4 again, but unlike 9. ... b6 variation, White no longer has the idea to play Qd6. }
10... O-O 11. h4 { Let's start our typical attack. } 11... Nc6 12. h5 Ne5
{ Black's plan is to transfer the Knight on g4 and to exchange the dark-squared Bishop. }
13. O-O-O
{ The logical move   13.Bh6?  would be a blunder due to  13. ...Bxh6  14.Qxh6  g5!  avoiding opening the h-file and intending to trap the Queen with ...Ng4.  15.f4  the only way to free the Queen.  15. ...Nxd3  16.Kd2  Nxb2  Black is a pawn up and the White King is exposed. }
13... Ng4 14. Kb1
{ In Kyiv, as in many other cities of Ukraine, where I am from, there is a place in the central park where chess fans get together. If you suddenly decide to play a couple of games there, then be careful, because some experienced 'amateurs' manage to play queenside castling and Kb1 in one move. On the one hand, this is cheating, but on the other hand, it is a sign of great positional understanding! }
14... Nxe3 15. Qxe3 Rb8 16. d4
{ The exchange of the dark-squared Bishop is compensated by complete domination in the center. }
*

