[Black "#12 Smyslov variation"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6
{ Black tries to save the move ...d6 in order to make the move ...d5 without losing a tempo. }
6. Be3
{ Of course, White disrupts this plan, and now the c5-pawn is under attack. The move ...d6 leads to the main variation 5. ...d6. }
6... Nd4
{ Black improves the position of the Knight and defends the c5-pawn at the same time. }
7. Nce2
{ This is a critical starting position -'tabia'. This move was played by the world champion Vasily Smyslov several times in 1946 and 1947. I think that this variation deserves to be named after Smyslov. We are trying to drive off the strong d4-Knight as quickly as possible. Black has several continuations. }
7... Nxe2 8. Nxe2
{ The first and most important question - is it good idea for Black to capture the b2-pawn? }
8... Bxb2 9. Rb1
{ This is the instructive variation of why the b2-pawn is poisoned. } 9... Bg7
10. Bxc5 { I find the c5-pawn more important than the b2-pawn. } 10... Qa5+ 11.
Bb4
{ Fortunately, we are saving the bishop and blocking the check at the same time. }
11... Qxa2
{ While almost all black pieces are undeveloped and the King is stuck in the center, Black spends a few tempos to win a side pawn. Not the smartest decision, is it? }
12. c4
{ With the idea to grab the space in the center and take control of the b5 square. }
12... Qa6 13. O-O
{ There's no rush, so we're calmly hiding the King and developing the Rook. }
13... Nf6 14. Nc3 { And now we begin to transfer the Knight to b5. } 14... d6
15. Nb5
{ We threaten to either take on d6 or make a fork on c7. Black is defenseless. }
