1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6
{ Black tries to save the move ...d6 in order to make the move ...d5 without losing a tempo. }
6. Be3
{ Of course, White disrupts this plan, and now the c5-pawn is under attack. The move ...d6 leads to the main variation 5. ...d6. }
6... b6
{ Black defends the c5-pawn and wants to develop the Bishop to the queenside. }
7. Nge2
{ The most popular move is Qd2, but I want to save a tempo in case we play d4. }
7... Bb7 8. d4
{ Now we see what was the idea of ​​the Nge2. We don't waste time and immediately play d4. }
8... cxd4 9. Nxd4 Nge7 10. O-O O-O 11. Ndb5
{ If we manage to occupy the d6-square with the Knight, then Black will have a strategically lost position. }
11... d5
{ A radical solution to the problem of the c6-square, but not without drawbacks. }
12. exd5 { Choosing the most important continuation - winning the d5-pawn. }
12... Nxd5 13. Nxd5 exd5 14. Bxd5
{ 14.Qxd5  is equally good but it simplifies the position.  14. ...Qxd5  15.Bxd5  Bxb2  16.Rad1  Threatening Nd6. }
14... Bxb2 15. Rb1 Bg7 16. Nd6
{ Transferring the Knight to the excellent square. } 16... Qd7
{ 16. ...Qxd6?  Accepting a sacrifice would be a blunder.  17.Bxf7!  A discovered attack!  17. ...Rxf7  18.Qxd6  +- }
17. c4
{ Of course, White's pawn structure is not perfect, but White has a big advantage due to the dynamic factors  (active pieces)  . }
