1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 e6
{ A completely different plan. Earlier we considered the lines where Black fianchettoes the dark-squared Bishop, puts the Knight on d4 and attacks on the queenside. In this line, Black develops the Bishop to e7 with the plan of playing ...d5. }
4. Bg2 Nge7
{ Black wants to transfer the Knight to g6. I am not even sure that the Knight on g6 will be placed better than on f6, especially since Black spends one more tempo. }
5. d3 d5
{ 5. ...g6  6.Be3  d6  7.Qd2  transposes to the main line of 2. ... Nc6 5. ... d6 6. ... e6 7. ... Nge7 }
6. exd5 exd5
{ 6. ...Nxd5  7.Nge2  Be7  8.O-O  O-O  9.Nxd5  exd5  10.Nf4  transposes to the main line of this chapter }
7. Nge2
{ Of course, we're developing the Knight on e2 with the idea of ​​increasing the pressure on the d5-pawn by Nf4. }
7... d4 { The only way to untie the e7 Knight. } 8. Ne4
{ Attacking the c5-pawn. } 8... Ng6 9. O-O Be7 10. Nf4
{ The Knight on f4 is very flexible. We're intending to play Nd5 or Nh5. For example, after castling kingside   10. ...O-O  11.Nd5  follows! And if  11....Qxd5  , then  12.Nf6! }
10... Nxf4 11. Bxf4 O-O 12. Qh5
{ Black's kingside is empty of pieces. We're invading the Black camp without resistance. }
12... f5 13. Ng5 { Creating really dangerous threats. } 13... Bxg5
{ Black is forced to trade his dark-squared Bishop to avoid a dangerous attack. }
14. Bxg5 Qe8 15. Qxe8
{ There is nothing wrong with avoiding the exchange of Queens by Qf3. It is rather a matter of taste. But Black has the bad pawn structure and the terrible light-squared Bishop, so I prefer to simplify the position. }
15... Rxe8 16. Bf4 { White enjoys the Bishop pair advantage. } *

