[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deviations on the second move"]
[Black "#1 2. ... e6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ The idea behind this move is to play ...d5 as soon as possible. } 3. g3 d5
{ Although this variation has been played by many grandmasters, I think I managed to find a pleasant advantage for White.   3. ...Nc6  transposes to 2. ... Nc6 3. ... e6 }
4. exd5 exd5 5. d4
{ The second most popular, but conceptual move! The pawn on d5 is an obvious weakness since it can't be defended by another pawn, so we fix it with d4. White's key idea in this variation is to play against the weakness on d5. }
5... cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nf6 { The only reasonable move. } 7. Bg5
{ We're pinning the Knight, the defender of the d5-pawn. A pin in itself is a good idea, though. }
7... Be7
{ It seems that White can immediately win the pawn by  8.Bxf6  Bxf6  9.Qxd5  . But a strong intermediate move Bxс3+  ! follows and it's time for the White to resign. }
8. O-O-O
{ Of course, this variation is very different from the standard positions of the Closed Sicilian. And I can't even call this position a closed one. Since the variation is different, then the plans are also different. Queenside castling is not a typical move for the Closed Sicilian, but this move is definitely good now because we are hiding the King and creating pressure along the d-file at the same time. }
8... Nc6 9. Qa4
{ The best square for a Queen is one from which it can't be kicked out! In addition, the black Knight is pinned. }
9... Be6 10. Bg2
{ Developing the Bishop and increasing the pressure on the d-pawn. } 10... O-O
11. Nge2 { With a threat to play Nf4. } 11... Qb6 12. Rhf1
{ Don't forget about the f2-pawn! } 12... Rac8 13. Be3 Bc5 14. Bxc5
{ Playing against or with an isolated pawn requires, if not a book, then at least a large chapter in it. But in short, when we play against an isolated pawn, we need to: attack it with all our forces; if possible, block it; trade minor pieces. The last point is especially important because this is the only way we can extinguish the enemy's attack fire. Therefore, we are happy to exchange the dark-squared Bishops. }
14... Qxc5 15. Qb5 { The exchange of Queens also doesn't hurt. } 15... Qxb5 16.
Nxb5 Rfd8 17. Rfe1
{ Followed by blocking the d5-pawn by Nbd4. We managed to prevent the activity of Black pieces and block the isolated pawn. Black is unlikely to be able to get rid of the weakness on d5, so White has a pleasant long-term advantage.  The annoying move   17. ...Ng4  fails to  18.Nf4!  Nxf2  19.Rd2  Ne4  20.Bxe4  dxe4  21.Nd6!  +- }
*

