[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Deviations on the second move"]
[Black "#7 2. ... e6 "]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6
{ The idea behind this move is to play ...d5 as soon as possible. } 3. g3 d5
{ Although this variation has been played by many grandmasters, I think I managed to find a pleasant advantage for White. }
4. exd5 exd5 5. d4
{ The second most popular, but conceptual move! The pawn on d5 is an obvious weakness since it can't be defended by another pawn, so we fix it with d4. White's key idea in this variation is to play against the weakness on d5. }
5... Nc6 6. Nge2 { Defending the d4 pawn. } 6... Bg4 7. Bg2 Nxd4 8. h3 Bf3
{ We have already seen this idea in the previous chapter. Black tries to exploit the weakness of the light squares. }
9. Kf1
{ This move doesn't look very nice, but we can easily hide the King with the help of artificial castling. }
9... Ne7 10. Bxf3 Nxf3 11. Nf4
{ Double attack on the d5-pawn and the f3-Knight. } 11... Nd4 12. Be3
{ Black still won't be able to save the pawn. } 12... Qb6 13. Bxd4 cxd4 14.
Ncxd5 Qb5+ 15. Qe2
{ We're saving our piece! We're not only defending against the check but also pinning the Knight on e7. }
15... Qxe2+ 16. Kxe2 Nxd5 17. Nxd5
{ Although the position is open, the White Knight is definitely not weaker than the Black Bishop. The White King is in the center, which is definitely beneficial to us in the endgame. Moreover, the d4-pawn is very weak, I'm skeptical that Black will ever be able to defend it. }
