[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Black plays 2.. a6"]
[Black "#1 2. ... a6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6
{ This move is often used by players whose main weapon against the Open Sicilian is the Najdorf variation.   3.Nf3  d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is a transposition to the main line of Najdorf. The main idea of ​​the move ...a6 is to advance the b-pawn as soon as possible and create pressure on the important e-pawn. }
3. g3
{ As before, we're intending to develop the Bishop on the important diagonal h1-a8. }
3... b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d3
{ We are playing the Closed Sicilian, so we're closing the game with d3. White could continue either with Nge2 or open the game with d4. }
5... e6 6. Nh3
{ Quite rare, but a very interesting move. The main idea is to keep the d1-h5 diagonal open for the Queen on d1. In addition, White has better control over the d5-square and has the opportunity to transfer the Knight to f4 or g5. I think this variation is a great finding for the Closed Sicilian player. }
6... Nf6 { The most popular and logical move. } 7. O-O
{ White already has a concrete threat - to play e5. } 7... d6 8. f4
{ In addition to the concrete tactical threat e5, which is not so difficult to defend against, white's key idea is to advance the f-pawn. I believe that this position is a tabia of this variation. Black has a lot of different continuations to choose from. }
8... Nc6
{ The most logical of all possible moves, and therefore the most popular. Though I have to admit, this logical sequence doesn't always work. }
9. f5 { Putting strong pressure on the e6-pawn. } 9... b4
{ The most principled move. } 10. fxe6
{ If we simply retreat with the Knight, then Black will close the game by e5 and we will no longer have the opportunity to play Nd5, as in the variation above. Therefore, we're choosing the sharpest continuation - the piece sacrifice! }
10... bxc3 11. exf7+ Kxf7 12. bxc3
{ What can you expect having only two pawns for a sacrificed piece? But we just have huge compensation. The Black King is terribly weak, half of the Black pieces is undeveloped and the other half, which is already developed, is awfully coordinated. }
12... Ra7
{ An attempt to involve the Rook to the defense through the seventh rank. } 13.
Rb1
{ At first, we're improving the position of the pieces on all sides as much as possible. }
13... Ba8 14. Ng5+ { It's time to start the attack! } 14... Kg8 15. Bh3
{ Not the most obvious, but amazing move. We're unexpectedly involving the Bishop in the attack, transferring it to the a2-g8 diagonal. This idea was the only reason the sacrifice of the piece was possible. }
15... Re7 16. d4
{ Black can't still defend against Be6, so there is no need to rush. } 16... h6
17. Be6+ { And now it's time to take the material back. } 17... Rxe6 18. Nxe6
Qe7 19. d5
{ White has not only a slight material advantage but also a total strategic domination. }
