1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6
{ This move is often used by players whose main weapon against the Open Sicilian is the Najdorf variation.   3.Nf3  d6  4.d4  cxd4  5.Nxd4  is a transposition to the main line of Najdorf. The main idea of ​​the move ...a6 is to advance the b-pawn as soon as possible and create pressure on the important e-pawn. }
3. g3
{ As before, we're intending to develop the Bishop on the important diagonal h1-a8. }
3... b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d3
{ We are playing the Closed Sicilian, so we're closing the game with d3. White could continue either with Nge2 or open the game with d4. }
5... e6 6. Nh3
{ Quite rare, but a very interesting move. The main idea is to keep the d1-h5 diagonal open for the Queen on d1. In addition, White has better control over the d5-square and has the opportunity to transfer the Knight to f4 or g5. I think this variation is a great finding for the Closed Sicilian player. }
6... b4
{ White has strong pressure on the d5-square, so Black is trying to kick at least one piece out of the center. }
7. Ne2 d5 8. O-O
{ It doesn't make sense to capture the pawn on d5 since Black will recapture with the bishop and it's impossible to open the d-file. }
8... dxe4 9. dxe4 Qxd1
{ 9. ...Nc6  was never played in tournament games, although it's the strongest continuation.  10.c3  Taking control of the important central square d4.  10. ...Nf6  11.e5  Opening the h1-a8 diagonal for the White Bishop.  11. ...Nd7  12.f4  Defending the e5-pawn and intending to play f5.  12. ...Be7  12.Be3  Qc7  13.Qc2  Followed by Nf2-e4. }
10. Rxd1
{ White has four developed pieces and he has also castled, while Black has only one developed piece. }
10... Nf6 11. e5
{ The Bishop on b7 is more active than the Bishop on g2, so it's good for us to trade them. In addition, we're grabbing the space in the center. }
11... Bxg2 12. Kxg2 Nfd7 13. f4 Be7 14. Be3
{ Although h3 Knight is rather passive on the edge of the board, we can easily involve it in the game by Nf2 and Ne4. White is slightly better. }
*

