[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "15. Model games"]
[Black "Adams, M vs. Sax, G, Germany 1998"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 Rb8 7. Qd2 b5 8. Nge2
Nd4 9. O-O b4 10. Nd1 Qc7
{ A general move without a concrete idea. You should first develop minor pieces, and only then the Queen at the beginning of the game. My recommendation for Black is  10. ... e5 }
11. Nc1 { White needs to avoid exchanging pieces to keep the tension. } 11...
Nf6 12. c3 { And the Black Knight is forced to retreat from the center. } 12...
bxc3 13. bxc3 Nc6 14. Bh6
{ Michael Adams perfectly understands that it's necessary to exchange the dark-squared Bishops in such pawn structures. }
14... O-O 15. Bxg7 Kxg7 16. Ne3 e5 17. f4 Ne7 18. Ne2
{ With the last move, White completed the development of the pieces and is ready for further actions. }
18... Bb7 19. g4
{ White is bringing to life the main plan of the Closed Sicilian - an attack on the kingside. }
19... h6 20. h4
{ 20.Ng3  It was a little bit better first to move the Knight to the kingside. }
20... exf4
{ 20. ...c4!  An excellent attempt to create counterplay in the center, but White still should have a slight advantage.  21.g5  hxg5  22.hxg5  Nh5  23.d4  With the idea to advance the f-pawn further. }
21. Rxf4 Neg8
{ Of course, it's an extremely passive move, but it is always difficult to find good ones in a bad position. }
22. Raf1 Qe7
{ Black transfers his pieces to the kingside, but his coordination leaves much to be desired. }
23. Ng3
{ Adams is not only improving the position of the Knight but also creates a direct threat of winning the Queen by Nf5. }
23... Bc8 24. Qf2
{ White is placing all heavy pieces along the half-open file. It's difficult to find better squares for White's pieces. }
24... Be6 25. g5 hxg5
{ 25. ...Nh7  It was a little more stubborn not to open the h-file and move the Knight to h7 immediately, but even in this case, Black's chances of saving are not great.  26.Ngf5+  Bxf5  27.exf5  Kh8  28.Nd5  Qd7  29.Kh2  +-  Complete domination of White pieces on the board. }
26. hxg5 Nh7 27. Nef5+
{ It's impossible to imagine tactics without a strategy, and strategy without tactics in the game of chess. From a positional point of view, Michael Adams played the game perfectly - he played the opening correctly, chose the right plan, and transferred the pieces to the best squares. When it's impossible or very difficult to improve the position, there is usually a tactical blow. }
27... gxf5 28. exf5
{ With the threat not only to take the Bishop on e6 but also to play f6. }
28... Qxg5
{ Black's best attempt to save the game. Gyula Sax creates a problem for Michael Adams, which Mike, unfortunately, can't manage with. }
29. Be4
{ Another confirmation that we are all human. Even such a strong grandmaster as Michael Adams makes a blunder in a winning position.   29.Ne4!  Ne4 is correct!  29. ...Qh6  30.Rh4  +-  And suddenly the Black Queen runs out of squares. }
29... Qe7
{ Exchange of mistakes. Apparently, Gyula Sax simply didn't believe in his luck.   29. ...Bd7!  And Black just has an extra piece }
30. fxe6
{ 30.Nh5  This move wins more quickly  30....Kh8  31.f6  Qd7  32.Qg3  And Black can't defend against the threat of mate Qg7. }
30... fxe6
{ I think Black resigned prematurely, White still has to prove that his position is winning..  Michael Adams demonstrated in this game an excellent example of a typical attack in the Closed Sicilian. An attack plan consists of several parts:  1. Get the pieces out.  2. Avoid exchanging the e2- and d4-Knights in order to maintain the tension.  3. Exchange the dark-squared Bishops.  4. Start the pawn storm on the kingside with f4, g4 and h4.  5. Open the f-file and place all major pieces on this file.  6. Transfer as many pieces as possible to the kingside.  7. Find tactics!  @@StartBracket@@30@@EndBracket@@ Adams,M @@StartBracket@@2680@@EndBracket@@-Sax,G @@StartBracket@@2570@@EndBracket@@ Germany 1998 GER-chT  ChessBase }
*

