[Black "Krapivin, A vs. Rakhmanov, A, St Petersburg 2007"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e5
{ 7.f4  My recommendation is to playf4  But the move in the game turns out to be our main variation. }
7. Qd2 Nge7 8. f4 Nd4 9. Nf3 O-O 10. O-O Rb8 11. Rf2
{ The move is a little weaker but makes sense. White wants to double the Rooks along the f-file.   My recommendation is  11.fxe5  dxe5  It's best to block the dark-squared Bishop with this pawn capture. }
11... b5 12. Raf1 f6
{ Too passive decision.   12. ...exf4!  Black needs to open his dark-squared Bishop.  13.Bxf4  And Black's position is even slightly preferable. }
13. h3 Bb7 14. g4
{ Correct plan! White begins to push the pawns on the kingside, creating an unpleasant tension for Black. }
14... Qd7 15. f5 Rbc8 16. Nh4
{ With the threat of taking on g6.   16.Ne2!  And Black has an unpleasant choice between exchanging his strong central knight or allowing white to transfer the knight to g3. }
16... gxf5 { It significantly simplifies life for White. } 17. exf5
{ 17.gxf5  This move is more preferable than the text one because it opens the g-file. Followed by Kh2 and the transfer of Rooks to g1 and g2. }
17... d5 18. Nd1 { 18.Ne2  And again Ne2 was stronger. } 18... Qd6 19. Bh6
{ Trading the dark-squared Bishops is also not a bad idea.   19.g5!  This move is better. The pawn on f5 is no longer under attack, so we can start active actions on the kingside without worrying. }
19... Ndc6 20. Bxg7 Kxg7 21. g5
{ A great move!! It is important to open as many files as possible. } 21... Kh8
22. gxf6 Ng8
{ Loses immediately.   22. ...Rxf6  is a more resistant protection.  23.Ne3  +-  Although Black's position is still on the verge of loss due to the weak King and the strong passed pawn. }
23. Ng6+ { Beautiful sacrifice of the knight, opening the h-file! } 23... hxg6
24. fxg6 { With a threat to create a fork on g7. } 24... Rxf6 25. Rxf6 Nxf6 26.
Qh6+
{ And Black didn't wait for a mate in three moves after Rxf6 and Bxd5.  In this game, White carried out an attack on the kingside step by step: he doubled his Rooks along the f-file, pushed his pawns along the f- and g-files, exchanged the dark-squared Bishops, and exposed the opponent's King. That's the way to play the Closed Sicilian!  @@StartBracket@@26@@EndBracket@@ Krapivin,A @@StartBracket@@2478@@EndBracket@@ -Rakhmanov,A @@StartBracket@@2473@@EndBracket@@ St Petersburg 2007 }
