[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 e6 6. Be3 Nd4 7. Nce2
{ This move was often used by world champions Spassky and Smyslov. } 7... b6
{ A rare move. Black defends the с5-pawn in advance and prepares to develop the bishop on b7.  7. ... Ne7 is probably the best }
8. Bxd4
{ 8.e5!  It was necessary to immediately exploit the weakness of the h1-a8 diagonal.  8. ...Nc6  Otherwise Black simply loses the pawn on d4.  9.Bxc6  dxc6  10.Nf3  White worsened Black's pawn structure and blocked the dark-squared Bishop. }
8... cxd4 9. e5 Rb8
{ Exchanging the dark-squared Bishop is still not the best solution for White. The e5 pawn is under attack now, so it is impossible to win the d4 pawn now. }
10. f4 f6 11. Nf3 fxe5 12. fxe5
{ The capture by the Knight also deserves attention, which is equally good. }
12... Qc7
{ 12. ...Bb7!  First of all, you need to develop minor pieces, not major pieces!  13.Nexd4  Nh6=  And Black has sufficient compensation for the pawn thanks to the advantage of Bishop pair and weakness on e5. }
13. Nexd4 Bxe5
{ The desire to win back a pawn at all costs results in undeveloped pieces and the uncastled King. }
14. Qe2 Bxd4 15. Nxd4 { Black has lost the advantage of Bishop pair. } 15...
Qc5 { Playing with only the Queen has bad consequences. } 16. Nb3 Qg5 17. O-O
Ne7
{ Black finally begins to develop his pieces, but it's too late. The Black King is stuck in the center, and the White pieces are ready to begin the decisive attack. }
18. Rae1 Rf8 19. Nd2 Rxf1+ 20. Rxf1 Nf5
{ With the threat of transposing into the endgame with ...Qе3. } 21. Nc4 Ke7
{ 21. ...b5?  The most tempting move in the position.  22.Qe5  But Black suddenly loses the Rook on b8. }
22. g4 { White is kicking the Knight out of a good square. } 22... b5
{ 22. ...Nd4?  is a bad move due to  23.Qf2!  threatening to take on d4 and to give a mate with Qf8. }
23. gxf5 bxc4 24. Qe5 Ra8
{ 24. ...Rb6  The only reasonable move of the Rook, which leads to the loss of the Queen.  25.f6+  Discovered check!  25. ...Kf7  26.Qxg5  +-   The earlier opening of the h1-a8 diagonal allowed White to include the light-squared Bishop already on the eighth move. White was able to take the initiative and quickly defeated his opponent thanks to an attack in the center because Black slowly developed his pieces.  @@StartBracket@@24@@EndBracket@@ Spassky,B @@StartBracket@@2565@@EndBracket@@-Hjartarson,J @@StartBracket@@2590@@EndBracket@@ Belfort 1988 }
