1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 e6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 d5 6. exd5 Nxd5 7. Nge2 Be7 8.
O-O O-O 9. Nxd5 exd5 10. Nf4 d4 11. Re1 Bf5 12. Bd2
{ The first deviation from our variation. I think it's better to play Qh5 and provoke a weakening on the kingside. Nevertheless, the text move move is absolutely normal. }
12... Qd7 13. Qh5
{ 13.g4!  Suddenly White had a tactical move.  13. ...Bxg4  14.Bxc6!  Destroying the defender of the Bishop on e7.  14. ...bxc6  15.Rxe7  White is distracting the Queen from the Bishop's defense on g4.  15. ...Qxe7  16.Qxg4  +- White has a big advantage thanks to two minor pieces for a Rook and Black's poor pawn structure. }
13... Rfe8 14. h3
{ A good move. White wants to grab space on the kingside with g4. } 14... Bf8
15. g4 Bg6 16. Qd5
{ There is no rush to take the Bishop on g6, it still won't run away. } 16...
Red8 17. Qxd7 Rxd7 18. h4
{ Grabbing even more space on the kingside and threatening to trap the Bishop by h5. }
18... f6 19. Nxg6 { Black was about to save his Bishop with ...Bf7. } 19...
hxg6 20. a3
{ I like this move. White is not only preventing ...Nb4 but can also play b4 at the right moment. }
20... Ne5 21. g5 { The pawn is escaping the attack and attacking the f6-pawn. }
21... Bd6 22. f4
{ If the e5 square were an outpost, then the Knight would be incredibly strong. But fortunately for White, the Knight can be easily kicked out of the center by f4. }
22... Nc6 23. Re6 Ne7 24. Rae1
{ White doubled Rooks and increased the pressure along the e-file. } 24... Kf7
25. Bh3
{ 25.Bf3!  It was more accurate to play Bf3 with a dangerous threat h5. } 25...
Rh8
{ 25. ...f5  It's not easy for White to make progress after closing the kingside. }
26. Rxf6+ { Winning a pawn with a discovered check! } 26... gxf6 27. Bxd7 Nf5
{ 27. ...Rxh4?  I think that this is exactly how Black was going to play but did not foresee a strong answer in advance.  28.Re6!  Double attack! It's impossible to defend the Bishop on d6 and the pawn on f6 at the same time. }
28. Be6+ Kf8 29. Bxf5 gxf5 30. Re6
{ The exact same idea. White is threatening to capture the Bishop and the pawn on f6. }
30... Be7 31. gxf6 Bd8 32. Rd6 Bb6
{ The poor Bishop can't find the right square. } 33. Rd7 Rxh4 34. a4
{ Followed by a5. Black resigned.  White managed to go to the endgame and exchange the light-squared Bishop, thus gaining the advantage of a bishop pair. After that White achieved a big advantage in space on the kingside and doubled the Rooks along the e-file.  And as usual, a strategically good play is followed by a tactical blow.  @@StartBracket@@34@@EndBracket@@ Rahman,Z @@StartBracket@@2523@@EndBracket@@-Abhishek,D @@StartBracket@@2286@@EndBracket@@ Mumbai 2009 }
