[Black "Yu, Y vs. Xu, Y, Beijing 2017"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 d6 4. Bg2 Nf6 5. d3 e6 6. Nge2 Be7 7. O-O O-O 8. h3
Rb8 9. f4 Nd7 10. g4
{ 10. a4  I think it is useful to play this move to open the a-file. } 10... b5
11. Ng3 Nd4 12. g5 { White is continuing the attack on the kingside. } 12... b4
{ This only helps White to get rid of the strong Knight in the center.   12. ...f6  The pawn on g5 is too unpleasant for Black, so it is necessary to get rid of it.  13.gxf6  Bxf6  And Black's position is even slightly preferable due to the strong Knight on d4 and White's small chances of a successful attack. }
13. Nce2 Nxe2+ 14. Qxe2 e5
{ On one hand, Black is attacking the f4-g5 pawn chain, but on the other, he no longer controls the f5 square. }
15. Nf5 exf4 16. Bxf4 { White is attacking the d6-pawn. } 16... Ne5 17. h4
{ The Chinese grandmaster defends the g5-pawn. } 17... Re8
{ 17. ...f6!  Although this move looks rather ugly, such domination of White in space can't be tolerated. }
18. Bh3 { White moves the Bishop to a more active square. } 18... f6 19. Qg2
{ Now, ...f6 is already a bit belated decision, since White successfully defends the g5-pawn with the Queen, coordinating his pieces. }
19... fxg5 20. hxg5 Bf8 21. Rf2
{ With the idea to double the Rooks along the d-file. It's important to improve the position of all pieces in the middlegame. }
21... Ng6 22. Bh2
{ Leaving the bishop on the h2-b8 diagonal in order to further attack the d6-pawn. }
22... Rb6 23. Raf1 d5 24. e5 Bxf5
{ 24. ...Nxe5  Taking the pawn would be too optimistic.  25.Bxe5  Rxe5  26.Nh6+!  Now it's clear why it is necessary to double the Rooks along the f-file.  26. ...gxh6  27.Rxf8  Qxf8  28.Rxf8  Kxf8  29.Qf2  And White wins the bishop on c8 on the next move. }
25. Bxf5 Nh4 26. Qg4
{ 26.Bxh7+!  It is rather strange that such a strong grandmaster didn't see a not very difficult combination. It is important to expose the King and open the h-file.  26. ...Kxh7  27.Qg4  The Knight has only one reasonable retreat square.  27. ...Ng6  28.Bg3  This very move might have been overlooked by White.  28. ...Kg8  29.Rh2  And Black doesn't have an acceptable defense against Qh5 and Qh7. }
26... Nxf5 27. Qxf5
{ White can hardly hope for an advantage after the exchange of the light-squared Bishop. }
27... Qe7 28. e6 Rxe6 29. Qxd5 g6
{ The only way to get rid of the pin along the d5-g8 diagonal is to move the King to the g7 square. }
30. Re2 Kg7 31. Ref2 Kg8 32. Rf6
{ And the game ended in a draw in a complicated struggle after 30 moves.   White managed to improve the position of the Knight, transferring it via e2 and g3 squares. In addition, White doubled Rooks along the f-file and advanced the g-pawn to the g5-square. Unfortunately, White overlooked the winning combination and Black managed to draw. }
