1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 a6 3. g3 b5 4. Bg2 Bb7 5. d3 e6 6. Nh3 d6 7. O-O Nf6 8. f4 Nc6
9. Be3
{ Not the best, but a poisonous move. The Chinese grandmaster sets a small trap.   9.f5!  is the move that we analyzed in chapter  2. ... a6. }
9... Be7
{ 9. ...Rb8!  It was necessary to protect the Bishop on b7 to prevent e5.  10.e5?  dxe5  11.fxe5  Nxe5  The Bishop on b7 is protected. }
10. e5 { Taking advantage of Black's error. } 10... dxe5 11. fxe5
{ After Be3, the e5 advance became possible, since the d4-square is under control and Black can't play ... Qd4. }
11... Nd7 12. Qg4
{ It is very important not to lose the initiative and continue to create threats. }
12... g6
{ 12. ...O-O!  I fully understand Vladislav Artemiev, who did not want to castle. It looks suicidal.  13.Bh6  g6  14.Bxf8  Qxf8  15.Qf4  But still, it was worth accepting the loss of exchange and trying to find compensation. }
13. Rxf7 { The first principle of attack is to open the enemy King! } 13...
Kxf7 14. Rf1+ { The second principle is to involve all pieces in the attack! }
14... Ke8 15. Qxe6 { With a direct threat to give a mate in one move. } 15...
Ndxe5 16. Ne4
{ And now there is a threat to give a mate in two moves - Nf6 followed by Bh6. }
16... Qc7 17. Nf4
{ 17.Nhg5!  It was more precise to put the Knight on this square in order to prevent the Black King from escaping to d8.  17. ...Kd8  18.Nxc5  Bxc5  19.Bxc5  Nd7  with an idea to play ...Kc8  20.Bh3  and if  20. ...Nxc5  then  21.Nf7!  that's why we need to have the Knight on g5. }
17... Bc8
{ 17. ...Kd8  Although White's advantage remains undeniable, there is no longer a direct win. The same idea as previously doesn't work because of the Knight on f4.  18.Nxc5  Bxc5  19.Bxc5  Nd7  there is no Nf7 anymore. }
18. Nf6+ Kd8 19. Qd5+ Qd6 20. Bxc5
{ Black resigned on this move. After   20. ...Qxd5  the mate in one move follows -  21.Bb6   Black played the opening carelessly and did not defend the Bishop on b7 in time. White immediately opened the h1-a8 diagonal and drove the Knight from the f6-square, after which White carried out a lightning attack. A great example of a chess miniature!  @@StartBracket@@20@@EndBracket@@ Wen,Y @@StartBracket@@2609@@EndBracket@@-Artemiev,V @@StartBracket@@2674@@EndBracket@@ Moscow 2016 }
