[White "15. Model games"]
[Black "Wiedenkeller, M vs. Lind, J, Karlskrona 1983"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 e6 3. g3 d5 4. exd5 exd5 5. d4 cxd4 6. Qxd4 Nf6 7. Bg5 Be7 8.
Bg2
{ I think it would be more accurate to castle Queenside, but this move is also possible. In any case, white's basic plan remains unchanged - playing against the isolated d-pawn. }
8... Nc6 9. Qa4 { As in our variation, the Black Knight should be pinned. }
9... O-O
{ 9. ...d4!  The most principled move, because of which I abandoned this variation. This is followed by complications in which Black should equalize without any problems. }
10. Nge2 Be6
{ But this move is just a mistake. Black plays too passively and slowly.   10. ...d4!  And again it was necessary to advance the pawn in order to prevent blocking on the d4-square. }
11. O-O a6 12. Rad1
{ The most natural move. We're attacking the d5-pawn once more and preventing ... d4. }
12... b5 13. Qf4 { The only move, but sufficient for an advantage. } 13... Nh5
14. Bxe7 Nxf4 15. Bxd8 Nxe2+ 16. Nxe2 Rfxd8
{ In a non-standard way, we exchanged the Queens and went into the endgame. When playing against an isolated pawn, it's quite important to exchange pieces in order to prevent counterplay. In the long run, a weak isolated pawn plays into our hands. }
17. Nf4
{ We're attacking the d5-pawn and improving the position of the Knight. } 17...
Ne7 18. Rfe1
{ We're occupying the only open e-file and chasing away the Bishop from defending the d-pawn. }
18... Rd6 19. Rd2
{ A flexible move. We have a nice choice between doubling Rooks on the e-file and the d-file. }
19... Rc8 20. Rde2 Kf8 21. c3
{ Taking on e6 was impossible due to the weakness on c2. Therefore, we're defending the c-pawn and threatening to win the pawn on e6. }
21... Rcc6
{ The Bishop on e6 is a terrible piece. Black is forced to spend enormous resources to protect the bad Bishop. }
22. Re5 Rb6 23. Rd1
{ 23.a3!  This prophylactic move should have been included.  23. ...a5  24.Rd1  b4  25.cxb4  It is important to take with the c-pawn to save the a-pawn, which will become passed.  25. ...axb4  26.a4!  This advance is the whole idea of ​​the move a3. White is creating an outside passed pawn on the a-file. It will be difficult for Black to stop the a-pawn and defend the isolated d-pawn at the same time. }
23... b4 24. Bxd5
{ Tempting, but a weak decision.  It was better to play just   24.cxb4  Rxb4  and  25.b3  with roughly equal play. }
24... g5
{ Returning the mistake.   24. ...bxc3  Black opens the b-file.  25.bxc3  Nxd5  It's always pleasant to exchange a Knight for a Bishop in an open position.  26.Nxd5  Rb2  And Black has more than enough compensation for the pawn thanks to the Bishop and the strong Rook on the second rank. }
25. Rxg5
{ White missed an amazing tactical opportunity.   25.Nxe6+  fxe6  26.c4!  I think that this particular move went unnoticed. White doesn't allow the opening of the b-file, along which Black would develop an enormous activity.  26. ...exd5  27.c5  Of course, this nice fork follows the capture. }
25... f6
{ A series of mistakes.   25. ...bxc3!  26.bxc3  Nxd5  27.Nxd5  f6  And it’s unexpectedly difficult to find a good square for the Rook.  28.Rh5  Bg4  And all White pieces are under attack. }
26. Nxe6+ Rxe6 27. Bxe6 fxg5 28. Bb3
{ Black's position is already hopeless. White is two pawns up and a Bishop against a Knight in an open position. }
28... bxc3 29. bxc3 Rc6 30. Rd3 h6 31. Rf3+
{ Black inevitably loses material.   This game is an instructive example of how to play against an isolated pawn. Although the play by both sides wasn't perfect, White followed the main principles of playing against an isolated pawn: to attack a weak pawn with all forces, to exchange pieces.   @@StartBracket@@31@@EndBracket@@ Wiedenkeller,M @@StartBracket@@2385@@EndBracket@@-Lind,J @@StartBracket@@2300@@EndBracket@@ Karlskrona 1983 }
