1. e4 c5 2. Nc3 Nc6 3. g3 g6 4. Bg2 Bg7 5. d3 d6 6. Be3 e6 7. Qd2 Nge7 8. Bh6
O-O 9. h4 f6 10. Bxg7 Kxg7 11. h5 g5 12. h6+ Kh8 13. f4 gxf4 14. gxf4 Rb8 15.
Nf3 Ng6 16. Ne2 b5 17. d4 cxd4 18. Nfxd4 Nxd4 19. Nxd4 Qc7 20. O-O-O
{ Our analysis stopped at this position. } 20... e5
{ The only move that doesn't lose immediately. All other moves allow us to play f5, kicking the Knight out of a good defensive square and breaking Black's pawn structure. }
21. f5 Ne7
{ 21. ...exd4  It was better to take on d4.  22.fxg6  hxg6  23.Qxd4  But White's position is more pleasant because of the weak King on h8. }
22. Ne6 Bxe6 23. fxe6
{ A far advanced pawn can be both a weakness and a strength. But the e6-pawn restricts Black's pieces and can be easily defended by the bishop on h3. }
23... Rbd8 24. Rhg1
{ White occupies the g-file and hopes to invade Black's camp through g7. }
24... Rg8 25. Qf2 Rg6 26. Bh3
{ 26.Bf1  Rxh6  27.Bxb5  And White's position is much better thanks to the two open files g and h. }
26... Rdg8 27. Rxg6 Rxg6 28. Qd2 { Attacking the weak d6-pawn. } 28... Nc8 29.
Bf5 Rg8 30. b3 Rd8 31. Kb2
{ 31.Rg1  Allowed to win immediately. White threatens to play Rg7.  31. ...Rg8  32.Rxg8  Kxg8  33.Qg2+  Kf8  34.e7!  Most likely White didn't notice this move during the game.  34. ...Qxe7  35.Bxc8  +- And the Black position is hopeless. }
31... Ne7 32. Rg1 Rg8 33. Rxg8+ Nxg8 34. Qc3 Qc5 35. a3 a6 36. b4 Qxc3+ 37.
Kxc3 { Thanks to the much more active King, the endgame is winning for White. }
37... Ne7 38. Bh3 Kg8 39. Kb3
{ White wants to play c4, breaking through Black's fortress. } 39... d5 40.
exd5 Nxd5 41. c4 Nf4 42. Bf5 Ne2 43. Bxh7+ Kf8
{ 43. ...Kxh7  44.e7  And the White pawn is unstoppable. } 44. Bd3 Nd4+ 45. Kc3
Nxe6 46. cxb5 axb5 47. Bxb5
{ The bishop is much stronger than the Knight in positions, where there are pawns on both sides of the board. Moreover, White has an extra pawn and three passed pawns. }
47... f5 48. Bd7 Nd4 49. b5 Ne2+ 50. Kd2 Ng3 51. b6 Ne4+ 52. Ke1
{ And White pawns can't be stopped.  Both players showed a good home preparation and theoretical knowledge. White maneuvered well in the middlegame, attacking the weak d6- and f6-pawns and threatening to invade along the g-file. Thus, Black was constantly under unpleasant pressure. Besides, the Norwegian grandmaster found the right time to go in the endgame, because the White King was much more centralized than the black King. Black didn't stand a chance to save the endgame. }
